<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Analyst: Credit-rating upgrade could come with debt reform  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- New York could earn its first credit upgrade
from Moody's Investors Service in a decade if state leaders
institute meaningful reforms to its borrowing practices this year,
a Moody's analyst says.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Kurtter of Moody's Investors Service said the state's
highest-in-the-nation accumulated debt of about $36 billion and its
frequent use of so-called backdoor borrowing are ''important''
factors in the state's current poor credit rating.
</P>
<P>
   Moody's gives the state's bonds an A2 rating, tying New York
with Louisiana for the worst rating among the 40 states it rates.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki has become insistent that the Legislature
institute debt reform measure in the 2000-01 state budget. The
process of adopting a new budget for the fiscal year beginning
April 1 came to a screeching halt this week, with legislative
sources blaming Pataki's hardened stance on debt reform as one
roadblock.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has proposed a borrowing reform package which includes a
cap on new general obligation and revenue bonding to 3.5 percent of
the state's personal income. New York's debt load is currently 6.4
percent of personal income.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's package would also eliminate the non-voter-approved
bonding called ''backdoor'' borrowing and require bonded money to
be spent only on capital projects and not to balance budgets.
</P>
<P>
   ''Given the current strength of the state's economy and its
current financial position, adoption of this debt reform proposal
could be a significant positive credit development for the state,''
Kurtter, who was once a fiscal staffer in the New York state
Legislature, wrote in a ''special comment'' on debt reform in
Albany.
</P>
<P>
   An increase in the state's credit rating would save taxpayers
millions of dollars because it would cost the state less in
interest charges to borrow money.
</P>
<P>
   Another chief Wall Street credit-rating agency, Standard &AMP;
Poor's, upgraded New York's credit rating twice in recent years.
But its latest rating of A-plus is still two notches below the
national average of state debt ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Moody's has declined to raise the state's credit rating,
however. Kurtter last year cited the state's heavy reliance on debt
financing, its overall debt load and projected future budget
shortfalls as the reason Moody's would not boost New York's credit
rating.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, Republicans in the state Senate and Assembly members
have all proposed debt-reduction programs. Kurtter said there
''appears to be a growing consensus that debt reform is needed'' in
Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Conway, a spokesman for Pataki's Budget Division, said
the Moody's report is affirmation of the value of enacting debt
reform measures.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a clear signal from Wall Street that the governor's
debt reform plan could produce a credit-rating upgrade for New
York,'' Conway said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, state Assembly Republican Leader John Faso
called debt the ''silent thief'' of state taxpayer dollars. He said
that the cost of debt service alone on all that borrowing has grown
from $1.9 billion in 1992 to $3.4 billion this year. Debt service
is the amount of principal and interest the state pays each year on
its outstanding debt.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the prominence of debt reform at the state budget
bargaining table, Pataki and legislative leaders have also agreed
to put a $3.8 billion bond act before voters this November. It
would fund improvements in roadways, bridges and mass transit and,
if approved, represent the single largest bonding act in New York
history.
</P>
<P>
   Some aspects of Pataki's debt reform plan would need to be
approved by voters in the form of amendments to the state
constitution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
