<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 00:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Attorney general made $6.2 million in 1999  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- State Attorney General Eliot Spitzer and
wife Silda Wall reported an income of $6.2 million last year,
thanks in a large part from the sale of properties in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the $5.9 million Spitzer earned from selling eight
cooperative apartments in Central Park South in February 1999 is
going to pay off the $9 million debt he incurred in his 1994 and
1998 campaigns for attorney general, spokesman Darren Dopp said.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer also reported making $142,492 as attorney general in
1999, according to federal and tax returns made public Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Spitzers also made $123,162 in income from rental
properties, also on Central Park South, and another $44,000 from
capital gains on improvements made to the apartments that were
sold.
</P>
<P>
   The Spitzers earned $465,840 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   They reported paying $1.3 million in federal taxes and $665,214
in state taxes last year.
</P>
<P>
   The couple made $16,056 in charitable contributions by check and
cash.
</P>
<P>
   Silda Wall, like her husband a Harvard-educated lawyer, did not
work outside the Spitzer home last year. The couple has three young
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Spitzer borrowed about $4 million from J.P. Morgan Bank during
his failed 1994 bid to win the Democratic nomination for attorney
general. He borrowed another $5 million for his 1998 campaign
against Republican incumbent Dennis Vacco, Dopp said.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the 1998 campaign, Spitzer acknowledged that his real
estate developer father, Bernard, had lent him money to pay off the
1994 debts. Spitzer had insisted that the loan did not violate any
state campaign finance laws -- campaign contributions from relatives
are limited to $100,000 or less -- because the loan was obtained
following his loss in the four-way Democratic primary.
</P>
<P>
   Dopp said a portion of the $5.9 million from the apartment sale
will go toward paying off Bernard Spitzer and the rest would be
used to repay bank loans. While the money will not be enough to
retire all debts, Dopp said it would ''substantially reduce'' the
amount the attorney general owes.
</P>
<P>
   ''He is determined to pay off the campaign debts with his own
resources,'' Dopp said. ''He is handling this by selling his own
assets.''
</P>
<P>
   A specific breakdown of the repayment structure was not
immediately available.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
