<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton and Giuliani courting upstate voters next week  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Hitting a key electoral battleground,
Hillary Rodham Clinton plans a three-day foray across upstate New
York next week while Senate rival Rudolph Giuliani is looking to
spend at least two days in the region.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady, after a Monday night fund-raising event in New
York City with President Clinton and Vice President Gore, will head
upstate on Tuesday. Over three days she plans stops across a swatch
of the Southern Tier and western New York, aides said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City mayor plans to address a Republican dinner in
Saratoga Springs on Friday and to be in Buffalo the next day for a
forum for Senate candidates being hosted by the Independence Party,
the New York arm of the national Reform Party.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, it was still unclear if Clinton would attend the
Independence Party's Senate forum.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton advisers, speaking on condition of anonymity, said she
is concerned about the influence of Lenora Fulani, a former leader
of the leftist New Alliance Party, in the Independence Party and
Fulani's backing of Pat Buchanan as the Reform Party's presidential
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has been criticized by some Republican leaders for not
spending more time in upstate New York, a region traditionally
friendly to Republicans, but resentful toward New York City
politicians. Upstate traditionally provides about 45 percent of the
voting in statewide elections.
</P>
<P>
   That situation only got worse for the GOP when Giuliani canceled
a trip to Rochester and Buffalo to speak to Republican women last
week because it conflicted with the New York Yankees' rescheduled
home opener. Giuliani went to the game.
</P>
<P>
   Mayoral campaign aides have said he does not plan to slight
upstate. They said Friday that he plans to give Law Day speeches on
May 1 at Syracuse University and at the University of Rochester and
to be at the Rochester Institute of Technology on May 3 for a
college forum edition of Chris Matthews' MSNBC ''Hardball''
television show.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans her own nationally televised college forum of
sorts next week, when she will be at the State University of New
York campus in Buffalo for a Wednesday night town hall meeting
hosted by CNN's Wolf Blitzer. The meeting will be broadcast live by
the cable network from 10 p.m. to 11 p.m. and by WNEQ, the Buffalo
area's public television station.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton plans a second nationally televised town hall meeting on
NBC-TV's ''Today Show'' on May 11 from 7 a.m. to 8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.hillary2000.org.
</P>
<P>
   http://www.rudyyes.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
