<HEADLINE> Amato Asked To Lead Italy Coalition  </HEADLINE>
By FRANCES D'EMILIO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Giuliano Amato, given the nod to form a new
government, is moving quickly to put together a coalition solid
enough to last until elections next year.
</P>
<P>
   His center-left coalition hopes by then it will be better
positioned to fend-off an anticipated stiff challenge at the ballot
box from conservatives led by media mogul Silvio Berlusconi.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday, President Carlo Azeglio Ciampi asked Amato, who was
a Socialist premier in 1992-93, to try to form Italy's 58th postwar
government after majority leaders pledged to back an Amato-led
coalition in the required vote of confidence in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Coalition leaders, after meeting Friday night with Amato,
predicted a government would be formed by the end of next week.
</P>
<P>
   After officials backed by Berlusconi routed Premier Massimo
D'Alema's candidates in regional elections on April 16, D'Alema's
coalition partners agreed that the premier had to go. They decided
to find a new man who could keep the coalition going till spring
2001, when parliamentary elections are due to be held.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alema, a former Communist who governed for 18 months, obliged,
resigning on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Smelling ballot-box victory, Berlusconi's camp lobbied Ciampi to
call elections immediately, but were turned down by the president,
who said he believed Amato's support was solid.
</P>
<P>
   Amato, who had been treasury minister, was widely credited for
helping Italy rein in its budget deficit. He wasted no time in
trying to win over leftist allies, including Communists wary about
pension-cutting.
</P>
<P>
   Ciampi could have called a special election, but that would have
blocked a referendum on reforming the electoral system.
</P>
<P>
   Amato pledged to work to reform the system in which a quarter of
parliament's seats are divvied up by all parties winning any votes
instead of by direct election. The system is blamed for a slew of
often bickering tiny parties that slow up the legislative progress
and sometimes bring down governments.
</P>
<P>
   An opposition leader, Roberto Maroni, criticized the choice of
Amato, saying it set Italian political history back 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to the minister's former ties to the Socialist
Party led by Bettino Craxi, the former premier who, tainted by
corruption scandals in the early 1990s, was in self-exile in
Tunisia when he died last year.
</P>
<P>
   Amato's integrity was never questioned during the scandals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
