<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Firefighters ignore fire because no one could drive truck  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A group of Queens firefighters decided not to
respond to a call because no one had taken a specialized training
course to drive a fire engine, fire officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Chief of Department Peter Ganci described the incident as
''disappointing,'' and said Friday that the matter was under
investigation. He did not comment on whether any disciplinary
action would be taken against the four firefighters and one fire
lieutenant from Engine Company 303 in Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have five members of the New York City Fire Department with
a fire to respond to, and for whatever reason, contractually or
otherwise, they felt it was not necessary for them to respond,''
Ganci said. ''For me, that was a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Ganci stressed that most city firefighters have driven fire
engines during their careers, but the department prefers to use
drivers who have undergone specialized school training.
</P>
<P>
   The incident -- first reported Friday by Newsday -- occurred
Wednesday when the company's engine driver, known as a chauffeur,
was injured, Ganci said. A fire department source, speaking on
condition of anonymity, said the driver had hurt his back sliding
down the firehouse pole to respond to a call earlier that day and
went on medical leave. That driver had taken the specialized
course.
</P>
<P>
   The company's lieutenant called the dispatcher to take the unit
out of service because no one else there had taken the driving
course, the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Ganci said the department had asked another driver -- who had
taken the course -- to go to Engine Company 303, but he had not
arrived by 3:29 p.m., when a fire at 107-33 159th Street was
broadcast, with a warning that there was a ''victim suffering
serious injuries which may lead to the decease of that person.''
</P>
<P>
   Technically, Engine Company 303 should have responded to the
fire because it was in their area, but instead, the dispatcher sent
nearby Engine Company 275, which got to the scene in three minutes
and 20 seconds, the source said. The fire was put out with only
minor damage done to the building.
</P>
<P>
   The fire was apparently started by a boy playing with matches.
He was the one referred to in the fire report as supposedly
suffering serious injuries, but it turned out he had fled to a
neighbor's house. He was burned, but not badly.
</P>
<P>
   The firefighters did not violate any regulations, but the
incident raised questions about their judgment, the department
source said.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials defended the firefighters' actions.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you drive a rig and you're not trained and you kill two
people, how does the department explain that?'' Capt. Peter Gorman,
president of the Uniformed Fire Officers Association, told Newsday.
Gorman did not return several telephone messages for comment
Friday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-22-00 0127 </TRAILER>
