<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cross-Border Hiking Trail Complete  </HEADLINE>
By JERRY HARKAVY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Maine (AP) -- The idea was as much philosophical as
recreational: Build a hiking trail linking Maine and eastern
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The intent was to strengthen ties between Maine and the
provinces of Quebec and New Brunswick, encouraging people to think
beyond boundaries.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph E. Brennan came up with the concept six years ago, while
running for a third term as governor. Though he lost the election,
his failed campaign gave birth to a project that would not die: the
International Appalachian Trail.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers who developed the trail are declaring it complete
effective today -- Earth Day 2000 -- fulfilling Brennan's goal of
finishing the project in six years.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it remains a work in progress, a case can be made
that the 650-mile trail from Katahdin, the tallest mountain in
Maine, to Cap Gaspe, Quebec, is, in fact, complete.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's arbitrary,'' said Dick Anderson of Freeport, president of
the IAT. ''When do you announce it's complete? It's hard to figure
out.
</P>
<P>
   ''You've got a guidebook, you can walk from one end to the
other, and we've put up 16,000 blazes,'' he said, quickly adding
that the trail probably needs a total of 40,000 of them.
</P>
<P>
   The 2-by-6-inch blue and white aluminum blazes are the only
bilingual trail markers in North America, Anderson said. They
combine the letters IAT, for International Appalachian Trail, and
SIA, for Sentier International des Appalaches, the French
equivalent. The IAT even plans to put out an 800-term glossary
designed to help hikers who speak either language converse in the
other.
</P>
<P>
   More than 450 miles of trail have been located, cleared and
blazed. About 175 miles now are along country roads, the biggest
stretch over 80 miles from Baxter State Park to Bridgewater, both
in Maine. Trail officials are working to relocate those sections to
mountains and forests.
</P>
<P>
   Such efforts have been hampered by lack of public lands as well
as landowner opposition and concerns about whether hikers and
logging operations can co-exist.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson says the IAT has been negotiating with key landowners,
including Canada's Irving Timberlands, for easements -- legal
provisions allowing public use of privately-owned land.
</P>
<P>
   ''We hope we'll eventually be able to work out a way to do it,''
said Anderson, a former commissioner of Maine's Department of
Conservation.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a brief stretch along U.S. 1 between Bridgewater and
Monticello, the road walks avoid busy highways. Many offer scenic
views of old potato farms and spruce-fir forests, the dominant
terrain along most of the trail.
</P>
<P>
   ''It gives people an opportunity to stop at the post office or
the grocery store,'' Anderson said. ''Some through-hikers say it's
good to be on a public road for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers are continuing work on other sections. This year's
goals include building additional campsites and adding about 5,000
more blazes.
</P>
<P>
   When first planned, the IAT was heralded as an extension of the
Appalachian Trail, the 2,150-mile footpath between Maine and
Georgia. That characterization was dropped amid concerns from the
Appalachian Trail Conference, which is not involved in the IAT.
</P>
<P>
   ''If people want to think of it as an extension, that's OK. But
we're not going to use that word anymore,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever they choose to call it, the IAT has enabled a handful
of hardy hikers to make a long walk in the woods even longer.
</P>
<P>
   John Brinda, a college student from Bellingham, Wash., made
history in 1997 when he became the first person to hike from Key
West, Fla., to Springer Mountain, Ga., then along the entire
Appalachian Trail, and finally to Cap Gaspe, a 4,400-mile journey
that took nine months.
</P>
<P>
   M.J. ''Eb'' Eberhart, a retired optometrist from Dahlonega, Ga.,
duplicated Brinda's feat the following year.
</P>
<P>
   Brinda had to follow roads or bushwhack through places where the
trail was incomplete, but Eberhart was the first through-hiker on
new sections in Canada that offered stunning mountain and river
views.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   International Appalachian Trial: http://www.internationalat.org/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
