<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hornets' Coleman Back in Playoffs  </HEADLINE>
By JENNA FRYER, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Back in the playoffs after a five-year
absence, Derrick Coleman claims he doesn't care who the Charlotte
Hornets play.
</P>
<P>
   But when he steps out onto the court tonight against the
Philadelphia 76ers -- the team he left two years ago to sign with
the Hornets -- Coleman is sure to have extra motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think there will be a 'Philly factor','' Charlotte
coach Paul Silas said. ''But deep down I have to believe he still
has an extra incentive to beat them.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman was excused from Thursday's practice, but returned
Friday and had what Silas called a ''good intense workout.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that's a sign of how he'll play in the best-of-five
series is unclear. For now, Coleman said he isn't looking at the
series as a revenge match.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't worry about that, it's just the game of basketball,''
Coleman said. ''I look forward to being back in the playoffs and
I'm excited about it. I'm just going to get ready for Philadelphia,
and, hey, see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   What the Hornets are hoping for is Coleman keeping his emotions
in check. He was ejected in the second quarter of the last meeting
between the teams when called for a flagrant foul on Toni Kukoc.
</P>
<P>
   It was the only time in four regular-season meetings that the
Sixers beat Charlotte, and the Hornets think they could have won
the game if Coleman had been in it at the end.
</P>
<P>
   ''Derrick was having his way when he got kicked out,'' Silas
said. ''If we'd had him, we would have won.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Philadelphia is hoping guard Allen Iverson won't be
slowed by his inflamed right elbow and broken left toe.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson's ailments kept him out of the 76ers' finale, but he
participated in back-to-back practices on Thursday and Friday for
the first time in months.
</P>
<P>
   It was all part of his effort to iron out the kinks before the
playoffs begin.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think I was rusty, and yesterday was my best practice
of the year as far as my rhythm goes,'' Iverson said Friday. ''But
practice time doesn't mean anything. I'm anxious to get on the real
floor. You don't win the NBA championship on the practice floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia coach Larry Brown thinks Iverson's long layoff -- he
didn't practice at all for more than two weeks -- should help him
play through the pain.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hopefully he'll be better,'' Brown said. ''If not, we have
other guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte guard Eddie Jones, responsible for trying to contain
Iverson, is certain Iverson will be healthy. Iverson had various
ailments during the four regular-season meetings between the two
teams, but still averaged 24.8 points against Jones' defense.
</P>
<P>
   ''If a guy is hurt, he won't be on the court,'' Jones said.
''Everybody is nicked up and has bangs and bruises, but I think
they are kind of overexposing his a little too much.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets have accepted that Iverson will score against them;
his 28.4 average ranked second in the NBA this year. Instead of
trying to stop him, they plan to have Jones slow him while their
big front line of Anthony Mason, Derrick Coleman and Elden Campbell
focuses on disrupting the rest of Philadelphia's offense.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he is hitting his outside jumper, there's nothing you can
do,'' Silas. ''But if you can slow him at all, I think you have a
chance because you have an opportunity to contend other guys'
shots.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-22-00 0141 </TRAILER>
