<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 01:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kings Optimistic Before Playing LA  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN NADEL, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Sacramento Kings finished the season on a
downer, losing seven of their last eight games, including the final
four. They dropped into the No. 8 slot in the Western Conference
playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as they prepare for their first-round matchup with the
top-seeded Los Angeles Lakers, Lakers star Kobe Bryant believes the
Kings appear to put the slump behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think everybody who knows Sacramento knows they don't really
care about that, they just come out and play,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kings guard Jason Williams supported that theory, saying,
''There's no question we never lose our confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings will need more than confidence to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a 67-15 regular-season record -- second-best in
franchise history -- and homecourt advantage throughout the
playoffs, the Lakers are favored to win their first championship
since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   History is against the Kings, too. In 156 opportunities since
the 16-team playoff format was adopted 16 years ago, the 1994
Denver Nuggets and 1999 New York Knicks are the only eighth-seeded
teams to beat a No. 1, eliminating Seattle and Miami, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Lakers enter the best-of-five series that
begins Sunday at Staples Center a bit wary, and the Kings come in
with some optimism.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all know this team, we'll have to play well to beat them,''
first-year Lakers coach Phil Jackson said. ''We have not yet found
a way to stop (Chris) Webber.''
</P>
<P>
   Webber, the NBA's sixth-leading scorer, averaged 27 points and
11 rebounds in four games against the Lakers this season.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's the heart and soul of their team,'' Bryant said.
</P>
<P>
   Shaquille O'Neal agreed, saying, ''He's a dominant power
forward. I think if we shut everyone else down, we'll be all
right.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal has been even more dominant. A virtual lock to win his
first NBA Most Valuable Player award, he scored an NBA-leading 29.7
points per game and averaged 35.3 points and 13.3 rebounds against
the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can't stop Shaq, you just do your best to keep him busy,
make him work hard,'' Sacramento's Vlade Divac said. ''To beat the
Lakers, we need to have a perfect game. We need to take care of the
basketball, that's a real key for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their late-season slide, the Kings (44-38) had their
best record since 1982-83, when they went 45-37 while playing in
Kansas City. Sacramento's success was mainly due to a run-and-gun
attack that resulted in a league-leading 105.0 points per game.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings gave the Lakers a tough time, beating them once and
losing three times, but by just three, one and seven points.
</P>
<P>
   ''Transition baskets,'' Bryant said when asked why the Kings had
success against the Lakers. ''Our defensive floor balance wasn't up
to par. We're going to have to nip that in the bud.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers believe they have put some bitter playoff memories
behind them, and the atmosphere certainly appears different under
Jackson, who coached the Chicago Bulls to six championships in the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In their three previous playoffs since O'Neal and Bryant joined
them, the Lakers were beaten 4-1 by Utah in the second round in
1997; 4-0 by the Jazz in the 1998 Western Conference finals' and
4-0 by San Antonio in the second round last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're a little more serious and we're better prepared,''
O'Neal said. ''We're playing a young, flashy, exciting team. We're
ready to get it started. I just hope we can bring our 'A' game
every night. If we can, we'll be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Game 2 at Staples Center won't be played until Thursday night
before the series shifts to Sacramento.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
