<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 02:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jurors Rule in Favor of Disney Exec  </HEADLINE>
By GARY GENTILE, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A federal judge will decide how much the Walt
Disney Co. must pay the estate of a late executive after a jury
ruled the company improperly coerced the dying man into signing
over millions of dollars in assets.
</P>
<P>
   The federal jury ruled 8-0 in favor of Robert Jahn's estate.
</P>
<P>
   The estate alleged Disney officials visited the AIDS-infected
Jahn just weeks before his death in May 1994 and forced him to sign
over $2.2 million in stock options, life insurance and deferred
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors rejected Disney's argument that Jahn gave up the benefits
to avoid being fired for taking kickbacks from vendors.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a moral victory. This is the appropriate verdict. And I
hope this corporation gets the message. It shouldn't conduct
business like this,'' Larry Sackey, an attorney for Jahn's estate,
said after Friday's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Dean Pregerson will decide later how much
Disney owes Jahn's estate.
</P>
<P>
   Disney had argued that Jahn relinquished his benefits orally in
December 1993 and in a written agreement in April 1994 to avoid
being exposed as a crook. In exchange, he kept his salary and
medical coverage, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Disney attorney John Quinn interpreted the ruling as favorable
to the company, because even though jurors ''found that the written
contract was unenforceable as a legal matter, they correctly
concluded that Mr. Jahn's promise to Disney to release his
non-medical benefits was valid.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe the case is over,'' Quinn said, adding that he
believes Disney won't owe the estate anything.
</P>
<P>
   Jahn was a senior vice president at Disney Motion Pictures &AMP;
Television Co., in charge of making trailers and TV ads for Disney
films.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Jahn's estate denied he ever took kickbacks, but
said he was on his deathbed and didn't have the strength to fight
the allegations.
</P>
<P>
   During the two-week trial, Quinn accused Jahn of bilking the
company out of $5.7 million by allowing subcontractors to overbill
for services. Lawyers also said Jahn funneled more than $300,000
through a companion by forcing one of the vendors to hire the man
at an inflated salary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-22-00 0211 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000422.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Military Shells Camp  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ZAMBOANGA, Philippines (AP) -- The military launched an assault
Saturday in the southern Philippines against Muslim extremists who
claimed to have beheaded two of 29 hostages abducted a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''A rescue operation is going on,'' said chief of staff Gen.
Angelo Reyes.
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate report on the condition of the hostages,
who have been held since March 20. The group, Abu Sayyaf, said its
members beheaded two male teachers Wednesday because the government
had ignored its demands, which include the freeing of Arab
terrorists such as the man behind the 1993 bombing of the World
Trade Center in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Reyes said the decision to attack the rebel camp in Basilan
province was made by a provincial crisis management committee that
has handled the hostage negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't have reports of rebel casualties, and on our part, we
don't have any casualty,'' Reyes said. He refused to give other
details, saying it would jeopardize the operation.
</P>
<P>
   Radio station DXRC said the rebels reported that the military
pounded their camp in Basilan province with Howitzer cannons and
mortars.
</P>
<P>
   The radio station, which had been off the air because of Easter
holidays, made a special 2{ hour broadcast early Saturday to report
the military assault.
</P>
<P>
   The station said residents of Maluso town could hear explosions
from nearby Sumisip, where the rebel camp is located. It said four
helicopter gunships were seen over the area.
</P>
<P>
   The group has demanded the release of Ramzi Yousef, mastermind
of the World Trade Center bombing, and Sheik Omar Abdel-Rahman,
accused of conspiring to blow up New York City landmarks. They also
demanded the release of two Abu Sayyaf members being held in a
Basilan jail.
</P>
<P>
   The demands were rejected by the Philippine government and by
the U.S. Embassy.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels originally seized more than 50 people from two
schools in Basilan on March 20 for use as human shields after
attacking an army outpost. Some of the hostages have since been
freed.
</P>
<P>
   The Abu Sayyaf is the smaller but more radical of two Muslim
groups fighting for an independent Islamic state in the southern
Philippines. It has been blamed for numerous attacks on Christians,
including the abduction of foreign missionaries.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. State Department has included the Abu Sayyaf in a list
of 28 foreign groups that threaten Americans at home or abroad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-22-00 0226 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000422.0033 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 02:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Strut Collapses on Qantas Plane  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- The landing gear of a Qantas Airways
Ltd. jet collapsed as it was preparing to take off from Rome's
international airport, the company said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A Qantas spokeswoman said all 303 passengers and 19 crew aboard
Qantas flight 16 disembarked safely after the landing gear failed.
</P>
<P>
   The Boeing 747, bound for Melbourne, was moving down the runway
when the strut gave way, causing one of its four engines to slam
into the tarmac, according to a passenger who described the
accident to Sydney's 2UE Radio network.
</P>
<P>
   The Qantas spokeswoman said the passengers were evacuated after
fuel leaked to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   She said the company would send a team to Rome to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   The malfunction is the latest in a series of minor mishaps for
Qantas. In the most serious, a Qantas jet carrying 391 passengers
and 16 crew overshot the runway during a landing at Bangkok airport
on Sept. 23. No one was injured.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
