<DOCNO> APW20000422.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 02:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NHL Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By HOWARD FENDRICH, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   The defending Stanley Cup champion Dallas Stars wrapped up their
first-round playoff series in five games. So did the Colorado
Avalanche and, surprisingly, the Pittsburgh Penguins.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Pronger, Al MacInnis and Pierre Turgeon made sure St.
Louis' series -- and season -- didn't end.
</P>
<P>
   Pronger snapped a third-period tie with a power-play goal,
MacInnis scored his first goal of the playoffs, and Turgeon added
two assists Friday night as the Blues beat the San Jose Sharks 5-3
to extend their Western Conference best-of-seven matchup.
</P>
<P>
   ''Their top players were certainly their top players tonight,''
Sharks defenseman Brad Stuart said. ''They did a good job of coming
out and throwing everything at us early.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis is trying to avoid becoming the first Presidents'
Trophy winner to bow out of the playoffs in the first round since
the Chicago Blackhawks in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday's other NHL playoff games, Pittsburgh edged Washington
2-1 in the Eastern Conference, while Dallas got past Edmonton 3-2
and Colorado beat Phoenix 2-1 in the West. All three of those
best-of-seven first-round series ended 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto plays host to Ottawa in tonight's lone game. Their
series is tied 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   No. 7 seed Pittsburgh upended Washington, which was seeded
second, by winning the teams' fourth straight one-goal game with
some help: Jaromir Jagr's cross-ice pass was accidentally deflected
into the net by Washington defenseman Calle Johansson.
</P>
<P>
   Jagr, the NHL's regular-season scoring leader despite missing 19
games, managed only one shot on goal through two periods.
</P>
<P>
   ''What do you want me to say -- that I was so lucky? You have to
be lucky to win,'' Jagr said. ''If they would have scored a goal
and we would lose you guys would have said that we got outplayed
and we didn't have a good team. It happens. It's hockey. Of course,
we were lucky. We're going to take it. I'm going to take it.''
</P>
<P>
   The early exit maintained Southeast Division champion
Washington's pattern of disappointing postseasons -- with the
exception of 1998, when it reached the Stanley Cup finals before
losing to Detroit. It also continued the Penguins' penchant for
ousting the Capitals. Pittsburgh beat Washington for the fifth time
in six postseason meetings over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh will face the Philadelphia Flyers, who eliminated
Buffalo in five games, in the Eastern Conference semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   At St. Louis, Ricard Persson's goal gave the league's top
regular-season team a 3-0 lead just 7:13 into the game. But the
Sharks, who will be home for Game 6 on Sunday, rallied to tie at
3-3, before MVP candidate Pronger put the Blues ahead to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Pronger, in the penalty box for 24 minutes in the first four
games, had only one minor infraction. MacInnis had been shut out on
21 shots the first four games, and Turgeon had been minus-3 with
only two points the first four games.
</P>
<P>
   Ladislav Nagy, a 20-year-old rookie, and MacInnis had the Blues'
first two goals, while Scott Young added an empty-net goal with
33.9 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Ricci had a goal and an assist and Vincent Damphousse had
two assists for the Sharks.
</P>
<P>
Penguins 2, Capitals 1
</P>
<P>
   Tyler Wright scored his second goal of the series in the first
period for Pittsburgh. Sergei Gonchar scored for Washington, which
lost at home for only the ninth time all season.
</P>
<P>
Stars 3, Oilers 2
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull, whose goal ended the Stanley Cup finals last season,
blasted in a slap shot with 5:03 remaining as Dallas eliminated
Edmonton from the playoffs for the third year in a row.
</P>
<P>
   The visiting Oilers had tied the game at 2 just 1:07 into the
third period when Jim Dowd's shot from behind the goal caromed off
the skate of Dallas captain Derian Hatcher and into the net.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher put Dallas ahead 2-1 with 7:15 left in the second
period. His score came 87 seconds after Todd Marchant tied it at 1
by stuffing his own rebound past Dallas goalie Ed Belfour.
</P>
<P>
   The winning goal was set up when Joe Nieuwendyk left the puck
for Hull in the high slot. Hull, who has more career playoff goals
(80) than any player participating in this postseason, wound up and
drilled a shot to the right of Edmonton's Tommy Salo.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's what I'm supposed to do,'' Hull said. ''That's my job.
I live to score goals.''
</P>
<P>
Avalanche 2, Coyotes 1
</P>
<P>
   Peter Forsberg's assist tied the game and his first goal of the
playoffs put Colorado into the West semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Forsberg, who missed the first 23 regular-season games after
surgery on his left shoulder and sat out the playoff opener with an
injured right shoulder, shoveled a perfect pass to Sandis Ozolinsh
to make it 1-1 late in the second period. Forsberg scored the
winner at 5:43 of the third by deflecting Adam Foote's shot past
Sean Burke.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado has won seven straight home games.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix lost its 10th consecutive playoff series, dating to
1987, when the franchise was in Winnipeg.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
