<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State making more rest stop space available for tired truckers  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- New York's Department of Transportation is
changing the rules on parking at the rest stops it maintains so
tired truckers can park their rigs overnight and get some sleep.
</P>
<P>
   The DOT is circulating a proposed regulation waiving the current
three-hour time limit for nighttime parking at its rest stops and
scenic overlooks for commercial truckers. The state instead wants
to let those truckers spend up to eight hours parked overnight at
rest areas.
</P>
<P>
   The rule change is designed to encourage truckers to adhere to
federal and state restrictions on how many hours they can operate
their trucks. Generally, those rules call for truckers to work up
to 15 hours -- up to 10 of them behind the wheel -- following eight
consecutive hours of rest.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't want them parking along ramps of highways and the
shoulders of highways,'' Michael Fleischer, a spokesman for the
state DOT, said. ''We want them to find a safe, accessible way to
take an eight-hour rest. It is safer for the truckers and safer for
the motoring public.''
</P>
<P>
   The three-hour parking rule at rest stops after dark was imposed
because they were intended to be places where motorists could get
out of their cars and stretch their legs or admire the view, but
not treat them as overnight campgrounds, state DOT officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the state Motor Truck Association, Bill Joyce, said
the proposed change in DOT policy was something his group has been
lobbying for.
</P>
<P>
   ''Part of it is there is just not enough spaces,'' Joyce said.
''People (truckers) are out on the side of the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Rules limiting hours of permissible driving often put commercial
truckers in a bind, according to Joyce. They must stop to get their
mandated rest, but they were sometimes being made to operate their
rigs -- in violation of the rules -- by police officers rousing them
out of rest areas if they exceeded the three-hour parking limit.
</P>
<P>
   ''They would wake them up and chase them out,'' Joyce said.
''But the problem is when they made them move, the trucker was
technically violating the federal hours of service rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyce said that in the absence of the state embarking on an
ambitious program to create new rest stop spaces for overnighting
truckers -- Fleischer said some additional space is being built,
often in conjunction with constructing state police satellite
offices -- the DOT rule change is a sensible alternative.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's utilize the facilities we have,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The rules limiting the hours commercial truckers can be on the
road date to 1937. The American Trucking Association has called for
the addition of thousands more rest stop parking spaces around the
country so long-haul truckers can safely park their rigs and sleep.
</P>
<P>
   The DOT will accept public comment on its proposed rule change
for next month and a half. It could be in place as early as June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
