<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 14:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Agents Didn't Fire at Waco  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- A simulation of the deadly 1993 Branch Davidian
siege showed that flashes caught on videotape were most likely
sunlight reflecting off debris, not government gunfire as claimed
in a wrongful death lawsuit, according to a preliminary report.
</P>
<P>
   Vector Data Systems, the British firm that conducted the March
19 simulation at an Army base in Texas, submitted its report
earlier this month to U.S. District Judge Walter Smith Jr., who is
presiding over the Branch Davidian lawsuit, the St. Louis
Post-Dispatch reported Saturday, citing unidentified informed
sources.
</P>
<P>
   Vector found that flashes produced by sunlight reflecting off
debris lasted considerably longer than flashes produced by gunfire,
the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   That finding would support the government's claim that similar
flashes seen on a 1993 infrared tape of the siege were the result
of sunlight reflecting off the crumbling complex, not gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   But an attorney for Branch Davidian survivors and relatives,
Michael Caddell, insists he does not have to prove government
gunfire caused the deaths of more than 80 members of the sect.
</P>
<P>
   Caddell says he plans to show the government was negligent in
not having fire equipment at the 1993 siege that ended in a deadly
blaze at the compound outside Waco, Texas. And he said his own
experts will contradict the conclusion that the flashes were
reflections.
</P>
<P>
   The fire started several hours into an FBI operation intended to
end a 51-day siege. The government has long contended the Davidians
themselves set fire to the retreat and caused their own deaths,
whether by fire or gunshots.
</P>
<P>
   Vector was hired to conduct the test by Special Counsel John
Danforth who was appointed by Attorney General Janet Reno to
oversee an independent investigation into the standoff and fire.
</P>
<P>
   Danforth's appointment followed revelations that the FBI,
contradicting a position it had taken for six years, used
potentially incendiary devices on the last day of the standoff.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-22-00 1434 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000422.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Struggle Over Florida Nursing Home  </HEADLINE>
By VICKIE CHACHERE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- Nelson Mongiovi's mother died in a nursing
home a year ago, but nearly every day he and his wife return to
visit other residents they know.
</P>
<P>
   Often, they find their friends lying in wet beds, or having gone
without a drink of water or without the necessities of human
dignity, like underwear.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, he and his wife, Gerri, blew the whistle on a
scandal at the Rehabilitation and Health Care of Tampa home,
leading to a change in federal law that bans nursing homes from
getting rid of Medicaid patients solely for financial reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the Mongiovis have no sympathy for nursing homes that
complain they are hurt by skyrocketing insurance rates and a
barrage of lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think there is anything frivolous about any lawsuit in
the nursing home industry,'' said Mongiovi. ''It's the only
recourse the public has. If it wasn't for the lawyers, who would we
turn to? The nursing homes? If they hear you don't like it they
say: 'Hey, get out.'''
</P>
<P>
   The industry warns that homes could close unless something is
done to curb lawsuits in Florida, which has 10 percent of the
nation's nursing home residents but produces 40 percent of the
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation that would give the nursing homes some relief from
lawsuits was filed in the state House this year but has not had a
hearing. Gov. Jeb Bush has not committed to calling a special
legislative session on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-nine nursing homes across the state were informed this
month their insurance policies would not be renewed by a company
that no longer wants to underwrite the homes.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen other insurance companies already have left the market,
leaving just five carriers, said Ed Towey, a spokesman for the
nursing home lobbying group Florida Health Care Association.
</P>
<P>
   The average cost of insuring a nursing home bed in Florida is
more than $6,200 a year, eight times the national average, the
lobbying group says.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the insurance problem is the industry's general
financial state. Five major nursing home companies which operate
about 20 percent of Florida's nursing home beds have filed for
bankruptcy in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, more than 1,600 of the nation's 17,000 nursing homes
have filed for bankruptcy since last fall, according to the
American Health Care Association. The highest rates were in Nevada
and New Mexico, where nearly half the homes owned by big chains and
affiliated with the association filed for bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   The industry argues that it's too easy to sue nursing homes in
Florida. Plaintiffs can win unlimited punitive damages and don't
have to go through mediation before taking the case to a jury.
</P>
<P>
   The average lawsuit settlement in Florida is $278,000, more than
twice the national average, according to the industry's figures.
Nursing homes blame trial lawyers -- especially attorney Jim Wilkes
of Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkes, who has won multimillion-dollar verdicts and has become
an outspoken antagonist of the industry, said if there is a crisis
it's one of the industry's making.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like a bunch of drunk drivers losing their insurance and
calling up the Legislature and asking them to change the blood
alcohol levels because they are getting too many tickets,'' Wilkes
said.
</P>
<P>
   There have been no notices of homes intending to close because
of bankruptcy filings or the insurance shortage, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   However, the state's most recent ''watch list'' of 81 homes that
fell below state standards includes 32 owned by companies that have
filed for bankruptcy or reported financial problems to
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't have homes closing left and right,'' said Pete
Buigas, the top nursing home regulator for the Agency for Health
Care Administration. ''As far as what to expect, who knows. We want
to be prepared for the worst.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
