<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Producer Alexander Cohen Dies at 79  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL KUCHWARA, AP Drama Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Alexander Cohen, a Broadway producer for nearly
60 years and the man who brought the Tony Awards to national
television, died Saturday of complications from emphysema. He was
79.
</P>
<P>
   A colorful, prolific showman, who was never shy of voicing his
opinions, Cohen was a product of the golden age of Broadway when
one man could put on a play or musical.
</P>
<P>
   ''Angel Street,'' Cohen's first production, was one of his
biggest hits, opening in 1941 and running 1,295 performances.
Patrick Hamilton's Victorian thriller, which starred Vincent Price,
was later made into the movie ''Gaslight,'' with Charles Boyer and
Ingrid Bergman.
</P>
<P>
   His last show, ''Waiting in the Wings,'' a Noel Coward comedy
starring Lauren Bacall and Rosemary Harris, currently is playing at
Broadway's Eugene O'Neill Theater.
</P>
<P>
   In between, Cohen produced scores of shows including the
legendary 1964 Richard Burton ''Hamlet,'' directed by John Gielgud;
''The Homecoming'' by Harold Pinter; David Storey's ''Home,''
starring Gielgud and Ralph Richardson and Peter Shaffer's ''Black
Comedy'' with Geraldine Page, Michael Crawford and Lynn Redgrave.
</P>
<P>
   Among his biggest successes were a series of small, intimate
entertainments, usually featuring one or two performers. They
included Michael Flanders and Donald Swann in ''At The Drop of a
Hat,'' ''An Evening with Mike Nichols and Elaine May,'' ''Beyond
the Fringe,'' ''Good Evening'' featuring Peter Cook and Dudley
Moore and revues starring Yves Montand, Maurice Chevalier and
Marlene Dietrich.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was as executive producer of the Tony Awards that Cohen
made his biggest mark in the theater, opening Broadway up to a
national audience. In 1967, the awards ceremony, which began 20
years earlier, was televised live on ABC from the Shubert Theater
and featured numbers from the best musical nominees.
</P>
<P>
   For 20 years, Cohen and his wife, writer Hildy Parks, produced
the show, which often revolved around a theme, such as the renaming
of a theater or a salute to a composer.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen also produced other television extravaganzas including
three ''Night of 100 Stars'' telecasts in 1982, 1985 and 1990, as
well as several Emmy Awards telecasts.
</P>
<P>
   The producer was not without his flops, too. Among his more
notable --and expensive -- clinkers were Jerry Herman's ''Dear
World'' with Angela Lansbury, ''A Time for Singing,'' a musical
version of ''How Green Was My Valley'' and ''I Remember Mama,''
Richard Rodgers' last musical.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, Cohen is survived by a daughter,
Barbara Hoffmann, and two sons, Christopher and Gerry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-22-00 1537 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000422.0053 </DOCNO>
