<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: Elian Raid Was Right Thing  </HEADLINE>
By SONYA ROSS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton was sound asleep when he got
the pre-dawn call: little Elian Gonzalez was on a plane, bound for
a reunion with his father. The president was heartened upon hearing
the news, and returned to bed.
</P>
<P>
   A half-hour later came another call. It was Attorney General
Janet Reno. The president thanked her. ''I'm very pleased with the
way she handled it,'' he told reporters later.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's pre-dawn wresting of the 6-year-old Cuban shipwreck
survivor from his relatives in Miami capped a tense week for
Clinton. He stood in Reno's protective shadow, away from the
intensity of the custody dispute around Elian, while Reno called
the shots.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was, in the end, about a little boy who had lost his
mother and had not seen his father in more than five months,''
Clinton said. ''So I think she did the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   For Clinton, the drama unfolded amid a family reunion of his
own. His wife, daughter and other family members waited Friday at
the White House for the arrival of Clinton's brother, Roger. They
were supposed to be going to the woodsy presidential retreat at
Camp David, Md. for the Easter holiday.
</P>
<P>
   But at 8:30 p.m. EDT Friday, the president was in the Oval
Office, getting a status report from Reno on negotiations to
reunite Elian with his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez. Roger arrived
shortly after that, so Clinton walked over to his residence to have
dinner with his family and watch a movie, said White House
spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   White House chief of staff John Podesta fielded updates for
Clinton. At 2:15 a.m. Saturday, he told Clinton that if the talks
did not progress, federal officials were prepared to take custody
of Elian. Clinton encouraged more negotiation, but approved a raid
on the Gonzalez home if the negotiations failed, Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three hours later, Podesta reported that the talks had
failed, Lockhart said. At about 5:30 a.m., Podesta called again to
say Elian was out of Miami; then Reno called at 6 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   That done, the president decided to get more sleep. He arose
three hours later, got dressed and, with eyes still puffy and shirt
collar unbuttoned, went before television cameras to give full
credit to Reno.
</P>
<P>
   ''She made the decision. She managed this. But I fully support
what she did,'' Clinton said. ''And it was clear from our long
conversations that we were in agreement about this.''
</P>
<P>
   At an air base across town, Elian was in his father's embrace
for the first time in months, and hugging his brand new baby
brother.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton rejoined his own brother and, with the rest of his
family, headed for Camp David about 3 p.m. EDT.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
