<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Banker, Opera Chief George Moore Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain (AP) -- George Moore, a former leading U.S. banker
and head of the Metropolitan Opera, died at his home in southern
Spain. He was 95.
</P>
<P>
   Moore was buried Saturday in the Guadiaro cemetery close to the
Sotogrande sea resort where he had resided for nearly three
decades. He died early Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The funeral was strictly private attended only by his surviving
relatives and close friends, said an official at the resort.
</P>
<P>
   Born April 1, 1905 in Hannibal ,Mo., he started work as a youth
selling honey and as a delivery boy for a delicatessen. After
studying at Yale, he jointed the Farmers Loan and Trust Company
which later merged with First National City Bank of New York, which
became Citibank.
</P>
<P>
   Moore rose to run the bank's domestic division and later its
overseas operations in the late 1950s and early 1960s. He retired
from the bank in 1967.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967, he became president of the Metropolitan Opera
Association and is attributed with having whipped it into shape
financially.
</P>
<P>
   In Spain, he is remembered for having helped promote Algeciras
port, located close to his Sotogrande residence.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his second wife, two sons and two daughters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
