<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 16:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tobacco funds lower than expected, projects not threatened,officials say  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- The good news is, fewer people are smoking.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is, as a result, there's less tobacco settlement
revenue flowing into New Jersey state coffers to fund anti-smoking
efforts and other projects.
</P>
<P>
   But state officials are not worried. There's still plenty of
money for all the programs they want to fund, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ''All things considered, the point of the settlement was to get
people to stop smoking,'' noted Peter McDonough, Gov. Christie
Whitman's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-April, the state received a check for $138 million, the
latest installment in a deal in which New Jersey will get an
estimated $7.6 billion over 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   But back when the settlement was reached in February, the April
payment was projected to be $150 million.
</P>
<P>
   The culprit? So-called volume adjustments, which allow the
industry to reduce payments when cigarette sales decline, as they
have steadily.
</P>
<P>
   ''The volume adjustments allow for a slightly lower payment than
the projection, with projection being the operative word,'' said
Roger Shatzkin, a spokesman for Attorney General John J. Farmer Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all understood it was a moving target,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   State policy planners took into account possible fluctuations in
the tobacco settlement payout when they set out a preliminary
budget for the variety of initiatives for which the fund would pay,
McDonough said.
</P>
<P>
   For this year and part of next year, those initiatives include:
</P>
<P>
   -- $30 million for anti-smoking programs,
</P>
<P>
   -- $70 million for expansion of subsidized health care for low
income families,
</P>
<P>
   -- $50 million to help reimburse doctors and hospitals owed money
by defunct HMOs,
</P>
<P>
   -- and lesser amounts for programs aiding senior citizens,
biomedical research, children and hospitals that treat the
uninsured working poor.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, starting next summer, $100 million per year of the
tobacco settlement money is planned to help fix or replace
crumbling school buildings around the state.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike constitutionally dedicated revenues, the tobacco funds
flowing into the state's general treasury are not legally tied to
any one program. They are mixed together with other general sources
of revenue, so there's plenty of money to cover the program costs
in this robust economy, McDonough explained.
</P>
<P>
   But just in case the settlement fund takes a true nose dive, the
governor added $50 million to the upcoming budget as a reserve to
cover the tobacco-funded programs, he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Fran Rappa, a spokesman for the state Treasury
Department, said the proposed budget for the fiscal year that
starts July 1 had estimated that the April payment would come in
around $140 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''We realized there may be a volume reduction. So the impact is
not as great as it would appear,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The settlement was always about reducing smoking, and youth
smoking especially,'' said Shatzkin. ''So in effect, some of
measures the settlement was based upon could be coming home to
roost.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
