<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Building Flies Old Georgia Flag  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DULUTH, Ga. (AP) -- The Gwinnett Chamber of Commerce has found a
way to avoid the controversy over the Confederate flag and still
stay true to its state: It's flying an old Georgia flag, one that
pre-dates the addition of the Confederate battle emblem.
</P>
<P>
   The Confederate emblem was incorporated into the Georgia flag in
1956, only two years after the U.S. Supreme Court ruled segregated
schools unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The pre-1956 version also displays the state seal on a blue
field on the left side, but on the right side -- where the current
flag has the Confederate emblem -- are three horizontal bars, two
red and one white.
</P>
<P>
   The ''current state flag is offensive,'' said Richard Tucker,
chamber president. ''It's offensive to some of our members, and
it's offensive to some of our businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chamber of Commerce in Gwinnett County, an Atlanta suburb
where blacks make up 5 percent of the population, had its grand
opening Thursday. Tucker said he received more than three dozen
positive comments about the flag in a single day.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to alter Georgia's flag have fizzled since a losing
battle in 1993, but a new movement for change has gained momentum
since a tourism boycott in South Carolina prompted the state Senate
there to vote to remove the Confederate flag from the Statehouse
dome. That bill awaits a vote in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi is the only other state that includes the
Confederate emblem on its official state flags.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-22-00 1628 </TRAILER>
