<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Albanians Protest Imprisonment  </HEADLINE>
By ALEKSANDAR VASOVIC, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   POZAREVAC, Yugoslavia (AP) -- The best-known Kosovo Albanian
imprisoned in Serbia appealed Saturday for reconciliation between
Serbs and Albanians in the volatile, U.N.-administered province.
</P>
<P>
   ''Revenge leads nowhere,'' Dr. Flora Brovina, a prominent
pediatrician and women's rights activist, told reporters making a
rare prison visit on a government-sponsored tour. ''I just wish the
situation would calm down in Kosovo. My message to all people is to
reconcile.''
</P>
<P>
   Brovina was sentenced in December to 12 years imprisonment for
supporting the ethnic Albanian Kosovo Liberation Army. She urged
her fellow Albanians ''not to forget times when Serbs helped us
when times were difficult for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Brovina was among more than 2,000 ethnic Albanians arrested in
Kosovo during the 18-month Serb crackdown on the KLA and taken back
to Serbia proper before the 78-day NATO bombing campaign forced
Yugoslav troops and police to withdraw and hand the province over
to U.N. and NATO administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Many others are believed held secretly by the Serbs, and Kosovo
Albanians insist there can be no peace in the province until all
are returned.
</P>
<P>
   Another prominent Kosovo Albanian inmate, former student leader
Albin Kurti, insisted he had been jailed ''because of my political
activity'' and not terrorism -- of which he was convicted last month
by a Serb court.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are political prisoners here,'' said Kurti, who was
sentenced to 15 years imprisonment. ''I do not recognize Serbia's
laws. I am imprisoned by the fascist regime of Slobodan
Milosevic,'' referring to the Yugoslav president.
</P>
<P>
   During the tour of the prison, located in Milosevic's hometown,
Pozarevac, reporters were escorted by a senior government official,
Dragoljub Jankovic.
</P>
<P>
   Jankovic refused to comment on the prisoners' remarks. He said
that 979 people from Kosovo are currently jailed in Serbia, most of
them ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights organizations have opposed the severity of the
sentences handed down to many of the Albanian prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe in justice but I did not expect such a long term,''
Brovina said. ''What have I done to be sentenced to 12 years in
jail?''
</P>
<P>
   Jankovic said the ethnic Albanians are all treated well. Kurti
said he was mistreated earlier, during the pretrial investigation,
but not in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups also say authorities have taken bribes from
Kosovo Albanians to speed the release of relatives held in Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   Jankovic insisted the government was not cooperating in any such
activity and blamed ''corrupt'' lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   ''One could conclude that for some people, ethnic Albanians are
a profit-making merchandise,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
