<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Mohawk tribe leaders sign new casino deal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- State and federal officials want to take a
close look at whether an uncommon deal struck between the Mohawk
Indians and a gaming firm can allow gambling on any Mohawk site in
the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to need to look at this very closely to see what
all the implications are,'' said Michael McKeon, spokesman for Gov.
George Pataki. McKeon said Saturday that the state needs more
detail on the agreement from the Mohawks as well as from U.S.
Bureau of Indian Affairs officials who also must approve Indian
casino plans.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement could be worth billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The deal between the St. Regis Mohawk Indians on New York's
northern border and Park Place Entertainment aims to allow the firm
to build, develop and manage any Mohawk casino in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   The Mohawks would receive a $3 million loan and a large
percentage of the profits from any casino, according to copies of
the agreement given to The New York Times by people who deal with
the tribe.
</P>
<P>
   The state doesn't have details on the agreement yet, McKeon said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki still hasn't given his approval to the tribe to build a
$500 million casino in the Catskills. The state Legislature may
also have to agree. On April 6, the federal Interior Department
approved a four-year-old proposal in which the Catskills
Development Group had planned to donate 30 acres to the federal
government in trust for the Mohawks.
</P>
<P>
   But whether the Mohawks' new agreement with the largest gambling
company in the world will be federally approved isn't known. The
federal approval was based on a specific site -- in Monticello -- and
with a different partner.
</P>
<P>
   Investment analysts who follow the gambling industry said the
rights to the Mohawk casinos could be worth billions of dollars,
but some industry analysts doubted that Park Place would ever build
a Mohawk gambling hall because it would undercut the company's
heavy investment in Atlantic City, N.J. It owns three casinos
there.
</P>
<P>
   According to the deal, Park Place agreed to begin building an
unspecified ''gaming facility'' within 36 months.
</P>
<P>
   Tribal and federal officials were unavailable Saturday for
comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
