<HEADLINE> Report: Blast Near Algeria Minister  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) -- Agriculture Minister Said Berkat
narrowly escaped injury in a bomb attack in northern Algeria, local
newspapers said on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The papers also said six people, including two soldiers, were
killed in recent violence in the North African nation.
</P>
<P>
   Berkat, who was on an official visit to the Blida region 30
miles east of Algiers, had just left Magtaa Lazrag when the bomb
exploded on Friday, La Tribune newspaper said. A civilian security
guard was injured when the homemade device went off, the paper
added.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Algerian soldiers killed three members of an armed
Islamic group in a mountainous region around Teffaha, 280 miles
west of the capital, Le Matin newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day, two soldiers were killed when they stopped at a
roadblock set up by Islamic militants in Lakhdaria, 50 miles east
of Algiers, the daily Liberte said.
</P>
<P>
   The paper also said Islamic militants on Wednesday cut the
throat of a woman and kidnapped her 20-year-old daughter in El
Marsa village in the Chlef region, 130 miles west of Algiers.
</P>
<P>
   Algeria has been gripped by an Islamic insurgency since 1992,
when the army canceled elections that the now-banned Islamic
Salvation Front was poised to win.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100,000 people have been killed in the violence since
then.
</P>
<P>
   In a bid to bring about national reconciliation, President
Abdelaziz Bouteflika offered a peace plan that gave insurgents
partial amnesty if they handed in their weapons by Jan. 13 and were
not guilty of rape, murder or bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the proposal, attacks occur almost daily.
</P>
</TEXT>
