<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Amato Assembling Italy Government  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Premier-designate Giuliano Amato was hard at work
Saturday assembling a new government, working the telephones and
firing off e-mails to potential cabinet members.
</P>
<P>
   He has said he wants to have a list of ministers ready to
present to President Carlo Azeglio Ciampi on Wednesday. Both Monday
and Tuesday are national holidays in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Amato is expected to ask the lower house of parliament for the
required vote of confidence on Thursday, then go to the Senate on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The center-left coalition claims it has the necessary votes to
win approval for what would be Italy's 58th postwar government.
</P>
<P>
   Amato was at his office Saturday morning and planned to leave
later in the day for an Easter holiday on the Tuscan coast.
</P>
<P>
   Ciampi on Friday asked Amato, the treasury secretary, to form a
new government following the resignation of Premier Massimo
D'Alema.
</P>
<P>
   Amato has said he will present a list of ministers shorter than
that of D'Alema, who had 26 ministers in his government, along with
a host of deputies.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alema quit after his coalition suffered a humiliating defeat
in regional elections at the hands of conservative forces led by
media baron Silvio Berlusconi.
</P>
<P>
   Berlusconi, an ex-premier, unsuccessfully lobbied Ciampi for a
snap general election. Ciampi, however, was unwilling to do so to
allow a May 21 referendum on ending chronic instability in Italy's
electoral system to go ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Amato hopes to put together a government that can last until
scheduled elections next spring, allowing time for his fractured,
demoralized center-left coalition to regroup.
</P>
<P>
   The 61-year-old professor of constitutional law did a brief turn
as premier for the Socialist party in 1992-93. He was widely
credited for helping Italy rein in its budget deficit and is well
respected in international financial circles.
</P>
<P>
   The Socialists were then under the leadership of the late
Bettino Craxi and were badly tainted by corruption scandals.
Amato's own integrity has never been questioned.
</P>
<P>
   Amato has said that unemployment and electoral reform would be
his top priorities as premier this time around.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
