<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hardened by decades of political fights, Florio takes his lastchance  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   EWING, N.J. (AP) -- For Jim Florio, the race for U.S. Senate
represents a last chance in a political career spanning four
decades and he is on the attack.
</P>
<P>
   It is a last chance not because of age. The former governor is
62 but at a recent breakfast for retired UAW workers here he
appeared as tireless as someone half his age.
</P>
<P>
   This is Florio's last chance because of the nature of the task
at hand: to resurrect a political career vanquished by Gov.
Christie Whitman 1993, over the objections of the leaders of his
own Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   No one running for federal office this year can match Florio's
experience, dating to his 1969 victory in a state Assembly race.
</P>
<P>
   Florio's opponent in the primary, financier Jon Corzine, is the
most untested of this year's newcomers, but is nonetheless seen by
many as the favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine has the endorsements of both U.S. senators -- Robert
Torricelli and the retiring Frank Lautenberg -- and of Democratic
State Chairman Tom Giblin. He has won endorsements in most major
Democratic counties in central and northern New Jersey covering 70
percent of the registered Democratic voters.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Florio is taking the fight to his opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Florio, a former Navy boxer, has not only displayed a variety of
attack moves, he appears to relish it. At a recent news conference,
he was asked if he was depressed by Corzine's advantage in party
support and spending.
</P>
<P>
   ''Depressed is hardly an appropriate term,'' Florio said. ''I
think Mr. Corzine has a lot of problems, problems that his friends
and his allies that are bought-and-paid-for will not be able to
cover up for him or help him with forever. At some point, he must
stand up for himself.''
</P>
<P>
   A week later, at a campaign event at Thomas Edison State
College, Florio taunted Corzine for refusing to debate him
directly, insisting on a format in which they gave separate
speeches.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you get to this point, you can memorize 15 minutes on
anything,'' Florio said when it was his turn at the microphone.
</P>
<P>
   ''Who do you want to send down there to stand up for you and
your children and the values that you all have: amateur or
professional, knowledgeable or not knowledgeable, forceful or not
forceful. That is the set of choices that people have. I am not
going to need any on-the-job training.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio gets agitated about what he calls Corzine's cash-driven
''hostile takeover'' of the Democratic Party. If the millionaire
Corzine is going to flood local politics and state airwaves with
his own money, Florio is going to try to convince voters to
mistrust him for it.
</P>
<P>
   ''My concern is that we are seeing a sea change in the way that
politics operates,'' Florio said after meeting with UAW retirees.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're having Wall Street generically come and acquire a party
in the way that they acquire a company. It is mind boggling,'' he
said, referring to millions Corzine has spent already to help
Democrats in local and state races, including grants of $25,000 to
Democratic county committees.
</P>
<P>
   ''You buy off the competition, you give a golden parachute to
somebody to make them your friend, whatever you have to do to
acquire the company. That's the mentality we are talking about
here.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If this occurs, this will not be our party for Democrats. It
will be a fully owned subsidiary,'' Florio said.
</P>
<P>
   But a Quinnipiac Poll in late March concluded that only 17
percent of registered Democrats were bothered by heavy spending
from a wealthy candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Political analyst Jim McQueeny said it is disingenuous of Florio
to attack Corzine for funding local organizations. ''(Corzine) is
doing the party-building he never did,'' McQueeny said.
</P>
<P>
   Most agree the backlash against Florio's decision to raise
income and sales taxes in 1990 wrecked the Democrats hold on power
in Trenton to this day.
</P>
<P>
   ''Florio, who single-handedly tore down the Democratic Party
right down to the local office holders, is now criticizing somebody
for trying to build the party up,'' McQueeny said.
</P>
<P>
   But McQueeny said Florio commands a solid base among traditional
Democrats in the unions and working class, perhaps as much as 40
percent of the primary vote. The fight on June 6 will be for the
final 10 percent Florio needs for victory, while Corzine must work
his way up from anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Since Corzine has made reference to his positive role as
chairman of Goldman Sachs, Florio and his staff have made the
investment firm a target, attacking a financial world where assets
are the only values.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two weeks, Florio has attacked Goldman Sachs -- and
by proxy Corzine -- for financing oil ventures for a genocidal
regime in Africa, shielding an asbestos company from paying sick
workers and funding mergers that threw thousands out of work.
</P>
<P>
   As for his own flank, the 1990 tax increases, Florio has
practiced his answer. After his UAW speech, he opened the floor for
''questions,'' only to ask himself one about the taxes and then to
spend 20 minutes answering it.
</P>
<P>
   He blamed Gov. Thomas Kean for leaving him with a $600 million
deficit, and explained the common sense behind raising taxes as a
part of a philosophy he learned from his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rent money would go in the coffee can on the shelf, the
Chase &AMP; Sanborn coffee can, because she said you gotta pay your
bills,'' Florio said. ''It was her value system, and it is my value
system.''
------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.florionj.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
