<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Giuliani, protesters blast decision to take Elian  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY McSHANE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Dozens of Cuban-American protesters marched
Saturday outside Cuba's mission to the United Nations, ripping the
Clinton administration and accusing Attorney General Janet Reno of
sending ''stormtroopers'' in to seize Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani echoed the angry complaints of
demonstrators, saying this was ''one of the saddest days that I've
seen,'' and also using ''stormtroopers'' to describe the federal
agents.
</P>
<P>
   ''They trampled the wishes of his mother this morning with guns
and with stormtroopers,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't imagine that the American administration has lost its
way so much,'' the mayor said. ''I couldn't imagine that something
like this could happen in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki had a similar reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very upsetting and offensive that people with machine
guns and fatigues would break down a door to take a child out of a
home in America,'' the Republican said. ''This is something that
would happen in the Soviet Union or Castro's Cuba, not in the
U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the mission on Lexington Avenue, a crowd of under 100
demonstrators chanted anti-Castro slogans, waved Cuban flags and
expressed disgust with the Clinton administration over the pre-dawn
raid at the Miami home of the child's relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstration started peacefully, but wound up with one some
protesters burning flags and crossing police barricades. One man
was arrested for assaulting a police officer.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let Elian be part of the American dream, not Castro's
nightmare,'' read one of many signs held by the demonstrators. ''Is
anyone listening to what Elian wants?'' asked another sign that
featured a picture of the youth.
</P>
<P>
   ''These kind of storm trooper tactics are the kind of thing
that's done in Cuba,'' said Rafael Ocasio, 42, of Queens. ''Clinton
is a hypocrite. He says he's upholding the law, but there is no law
in his administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Ocasio said the image of the cowering child in a closet beside a
rifle-toting soldier ''will stay frozen in my mind for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Another demonstrator, Juan Guitierrez of the Cuban-American
National Foundation, said he planned a trip to Washington to
express his anger over the decision to grab the boy.
</P>
<P>
   ''America and all the world witnessed this despicable act,''
Guitierrez said. ''The Clinton administration sent storm troopers
into the house of a humble family.
</P>
<P>
   ''America is a beacon of democracy for all the people of the
world. At 5:15 a.m., that beacon went out.''
</P>
<P>
   The sudden decision to take custody of the 6-year-old boy early
Saturday morning managed to make allies of Giuliani and Democratic
state Sen. David Paterson.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think their judgment was outrageous,'' Paterson said of the
Clinton Administration. ''What has the government learned since
Waco and Ruby Ridge?''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, a spokesman for Democratic U.S. Senate candidate
Hillary Clinton, attacked the mayor rather than comment on the
decision to take the boy.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm shocked that the Mayor would call United States law
enforcement officers 'stormtroopers,''' Wolfson said. ''Rudy
Giuliani's angry rhetoric is divisive and wrong.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
