<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.J. Cuban community block highway, march in streets after raid onElian  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNION CITY, N.J. (AP) -- More than 150 people in the nation's
second-largest Cuban-American community blocked a highway, marched
in the streets and said they were ashamed to be American Saturday
after the government took Elian Gonzalez from his Miami relatives'
home.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was in tears,'' Rosa Grabe de Peralta said. ''I thought that
this was the land of the free, but apparently it's not.''
</P>
<P>
   Waving Cuban and American flags and carrying signs that read
''Clinton and Reno are kidnappers'' and ''Clinton and Castro --
Perfect Together,'' protesters marched down a highway ramp onto
Interstate 495 and blocked hundreds of cars in both directions
about a mile from the New Jersey entrance to the Lincoln Tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Three boys who appeared to be about 8 or 10 years old lay on the
southbound side of the highway in front of a Greyhound bus as one
man with a microphone screamed continuously, ''Free Elian!'' and
''Freedom!''
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrators dispersed after 20 minutes, the time that the
Lincoln Tunnel was closed to both New York City and New Jersey
drivers. No one was hurt or arrested, said Port Authority of New
York and New Jersey Sgt. Stephen Prospero.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Mendez, 30, of Weehawken waved two large Cuban and
American flags in the middle of traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ''When 800,000 people feel the same way, it's for a reason,''
Mendez said, referring to the nation's Cuban-American community.
''I'm ashamed to be American today.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the type of situation I worked hard to avoid,'' said
U.S. Sen. Robert Torricelli, who was a key participant in
negotiations to reunite the boy with his father last week.
</P>
<P>
   In a carefully worded statement that did not blame anyone for
the raid, Torricelli said, ''We are a nation of laws that respects
freedom and human dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Robert Menendez, a Cuban American who also has
participated in negotiations, called the raid ''a despicable use of
the force of the federal government.''
</P>
<P>
   ''To take a child out at gunpoint in the middle of the night,
awakened from his sleep, with masks on, reminds me of the tactics
of Castro's dictatorship,'' said Menendez, D-N.J.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference at his Union City office, Menendez said the
family's negotiators were ''on the verge of an agreement'' with the
government to release Elian when the raid began.
</P>
<P>
   Residents in Hudson County, which is home to about 150,000
Cuban-Americans, awoke to news of Elian's taking that blared on
Spanish language television and radio in local businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ''President Clinton is following Fidel Castro's orders,'' said
Luis Nunez, 48, sitting inside the El Artesano restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   He said Clinton and Attorney General Janet Reno made a deal with
the Cuban government to remove the boy by force, rather than allow
the boy's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, to come to Florida to take
him.
</P>
<P>
   Holding a copy of an Associated Press photograph of an agent in
riot gear pointing a gun near Elian, 10-year-old Amanda Perez said:
''If Elian's father really loved him, he would have come from the
beginning, not coming to get him like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many said they expected the government to take the boy,
they were surprised it occurred on the holy day before Easter.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are preparing to go to church and they come in and take
him,'' said Sergio Alonso.
</P>
<P>
   Community leaders who had scrambled to put together a protest
Saturday afternoon in Union City's business district decided to
scrap that after the march on the Lincoln Tunnel. Instead, at least
150 demonstrators boarded buses headed for New York City to attend
a previously planned vigil outside the Cuban Mission.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the afternoon, about 100 younger people began marching
in the streets again, chanting in Spanish, ''Clinton, Fidel,
Husband and Wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Some residents understood the government's action.
</P>
<P>
   ''You've got a family laughing at the attorney general, and
sooner or later you've got to show them some authority,'' said
Roland Rolo, 44, sipping coffee in a Union City cafe. ''The family
overestimated their position of power.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
