<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Compares Clinton to Castro  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM C. MANN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional Republican leaders accused the
Clinton administration of using Fidel Castro's tactics to snatch
Elian Gonzalez from relatives in Miami on Saturday to be reunited
with his father. A Cuban-born congressman is demanding a
congressional hearing about President Clinton's ''most cowardly
act.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott, R-Miss., the Senate majority leader, said the
armed raid ''clearly was not justified'' and blamed the president.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I awoke in my hometown with my family today -- Easter
weekend -- and learned of the tactics that had been used to seize
Elian Gonzalez, my first thought was that this could only happen in
Castro's Cuba,'' Lott said. ''President Clinton should not have
allowed this to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom DeLay, the third-ranking Republican in the House,
accused the administration of kidnapping the boy, ''more
reminiscent of Castro's communist Cuba than the America I thought I
knew.''
</P>
<P>
   He apologized ''to all Americans who are morally offended'' by
the raid.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, spokesman Joe Lockhart accused Republicans
of ignoring repeated Clinton pleas to keep politics out of the
Elian saga.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's disappointing that those leaders today continued that
effort to exploit the case of a 6-year-old boy for political
purposes,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno said she sent in Immigration and
Naturalization Service agents and federal marshals only after
negotiations broke down with Elian's Miami relatives to surrender
the boy to his father.
</P>
<P>
   ''Juan Miguel Gonzalez and Janet Reno have mustered
extraordinary patience in waiting this long,'' said Sen. Patrick
Leahy of Vermont, ranking Democrat on the Senate Judiciary
Committee, which handles Justice Department matters.
</P>
<P>
   Reno and the raiding party ''acted professionally as they did
their duty to uphold the law,'' Leahy said. ''It is unfortunate
that the Miami relatives made it necessary to send federal agents
to remove Elian.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans disagreed strenuously with that line of reasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Cuban-born Miamian Rep. Lincoln Diaz-Balart said he will demand
a congressional investigation of Reno and Clinton's conduct and
wants to know what was behind the raid. ''I accuse William
Jefferson Clinton ... of committing his most cowardly act,''
Diaz-Balart said.
</P>
<P>
   Another Florida Republican, Sen. Connie Mack, expressed
repulsion and outrage and said the predawn raid on the house where
Elian has lived since surviving a Thanksgiving boat wreck marked
''a tragic day in the United States of America.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Christopher Shays, a Connecticut Republican, sharply
criticized the Clinton administration Saturday for its seizure of
the boy.
</P>
<P>
   ''The forced abduction of Elian Gonzalez at five o'clock in the
morning on a sacred holiday with guns drawn was dangerous and
reckless,'' Shays said. ''While Elian needed to be reunited with
his father, there is a process that should have been followed that
protects his life and those who care deeply about him on all
sides.''
</P>
<P>
   The episode also had an impact on the presidential election
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement from Al Gore's campaign office in Nashville,
Tenn., the vice president repeated his previous stand that ''this
issue should have been handled through a family court and with the
family coming together.''
</P>
<P>
   As street violence struck parts of Miami in protest to the boy's
seizure, the presumed Democratic nominee appealed to ''all
Americans, no matter what their position on this issue, to obey the
rule of law.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's likely GOP opponent in November, Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, blamed Gore with Clinton for deciding to resolve a custody
dispute ''in the terror of middle-of-the-night raids.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The moral authority of our law comes from the understanding it
will be applied in a fair and measured way,'' Bush said. ''The
chilling picture of a little boy being removed from his home at
gunpoint defies the values of America.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's brother Jeb, Florida's governor, said Clinton assured him
the administration intended to negotiate a settlement. ''I was
surprised that the forcible removal of Elian took place when it
did, in light of the recent positive developments to resolve the
matter peacefully,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his disappointment over the raid, however, the Florida
governor urged Miami's Cuban community not to infringe on the
rights of others with their protests or risk public safety. He said
state law enforcers would be available, if needed, to keep the
peace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
