<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pope Leads Open-Air Vigil  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   VATICAN CITY (AP) -- Pope John Paul II led thousands of faithful
Saturday in an open-air candlelit vigil for the approach of Easter,
lighting a twinkling flame shared hand-to-hand as twilight fell
over St. Peter's Square.
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony, normally held in the darkness of St. Peter's
Basilica, moved outside for the Holy Year.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 20,000 worshippers gathered before the
flower-banked steps of the basilica, sunset lighting up jet trails
in the apricot sky behind the dome on a warm spring evening.
</P>
<P>
   ''Christ is risen!'' John Paul proclaimed to the crowd as
darkness settled. ''We proclaim this witness to the world, so that
the joy which is ours will reach countless other hearts, kindling
in them the light that does not disappoint.''
</P>
<P>
   The ceremony is the most solemn of the Catholic liturgical year,
marking off the final dark hours before the exultation of Easter
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The 79-year-old pope's strength showed no sign of flagging
through the long ceremony, which leaves him only a short night of
sleep before Easter Mass. He waited attentively as each of eight
lay people approached his throne on the steps, baptizing them in a
fixture of the Easter vigil.
</P>
<P>
   Often those baptized are chosen for the symbolism of their
nationality. This year, as in recent ones, China was among the
countries selected -- a move that emphasizes the Vatican's
sovereignty over China's Catholics. China does not recognize that
authority.
</P>
<P>
   The pope in the past has remarked on political strife and other
troubles facing the countries of those baptized. This year, his
message was strictly religious -- celebrating the most central event
to Christianity, the resurrection of Christ.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
