<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudis Refute Meningitis Reports  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) -- Saudi Arabia denied reports Saturday
that an outbreak of meningitis among Muslim pilgrims who recently
traveled to Mecca had originated in the kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no proof that the cases reported in some European and
African countries originated in Mecca or Saudi Arabia,'' said a
Health Ministry official on condition he not be identified.
</P>
<P>
   The World Health Organization said Thursday it had recorded 250
cases of meningitis it believes is linked to the pilgrimage to
Muslim shrines, called the hajj. The U.S. Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention said three of those people were from New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-five of those diagnosed have died.
</P>
<P>
   The reports began about a week ago when Britain and France
diagnosed meningitis in pilgrims who had returned Saudi Arabia.
Last week, Saudi Arabia denied a report that two people who had
died in France from meningitis had contracted it while performing
the pilgrimage or from returned pilgrims.
</P>
<P>
   The Saudi health official said the number of meningitis cases
registered in the kingdom last year was 11, ''a low figure compared
to other countries and that is due to the strict preventive
measures taken by Saudi Arabia.''
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Arabia requires visitors to produce documents certifying
that they have been vaccinated against contagious diseases such as
meningitis.
</P>
<P>
   About 1.3 million pilgrims traveled to Mecca last month for the
pilgrimage, which every able-bodied Muslim is expected to perform
at least once.
</P>
<P>
   Bacterial meningitis is a serious and often deadly infection of
the fluid and membranes covering the brain and spinal cord. Its
symptoms include stiff neck, fever, intense headache, nausea,
vomiting and a purplish rash. It is spread through coughing,
kissing and other close contact.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
