<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Environmentalists see progress, problems in NJ on 30th anniversary  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Citing worsening air and water quality, as
well as sprawl, New Jersey environmentalists said this year's Earth
Day was as much a call to action as a celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ''In some ways the quality of the pollution is less severe,''
David Pringle of the New Jersey Environmental Federation told the
Courier News of Bridgewater for Saturday's editions. ''But the
quantity and the long-term impacts are even worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite government efforts to preserve open space, such as the
plan to save 1 million acres in a decade, activists are divided
over whether the state's environmental situation has improved.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists complain that government officials have failed
to enact a waste water plan that will prevent construction of sewer
lines in undeveloped areas.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some say official discussions about the proposed
plan have indicated that the rules will be weak once they pass.
</P>
<P>
   ''Full-time environmentalists want to hide under our desks on
Earth Day,'' Bill Neil, conservation director for the New Jersey
Audubon Society, told The Times of Trenton for Saturday's editions.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Gov. Christie Whitman received a ''National Award for
Environmental Sustainability'' from Renew America, a national
environmental organization. She was recognized by the same group
for her support of ''smart growth'' about a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   But New Jersey's population is increasing in many areas, and
environmentalists say they fear rampant development is not far
behind.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the number of people living in Ocean County has
more than doubled since Earth Day 1970, from 208,470 to a projected
490,000 this year. Some projections expect it to reach 576,000 by
2020.
</P>
<P>
   Monmouth County's population, now about 614,000, is expected to
reach 705,000 by 2020.
</P>
<P>
   William deCamp Jr., president of Save Barnegat Bay, told the
Asbury Park Press of Neptune in Saturday's editions that he's
pessimistic about the future if current trends hold.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Whitman's efforts to curb sprawl, deCamp blamed her
administration for failing to prevent development along the coast.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we can't find some mechanism for slowing down rampant
overdevelopment, the future for nature in our county cannot be
bright,'' he said. ''I'm pleased to note that Gov. Whitman's term
runs out in less than two years, so there is some hope there.''
</P>
<P>
   Jayne O'Conner, a spokesman for the governor, said Whitman has
launched one of the most ambitious land preservation plans in the
country and is committed to the state's environment.
</P>
<P>
   And some environmentalists say they've seen attitudes -- both
official and unofficial -- shift in favor of preserving natural
resources.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Forest, a member of Monmouth County Friends of Clearwater,
said he sees more awareness of the need for balance between the
needs of residents and the importance of the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's in our best interests to have a balance, because nobody
is going to be happy if we don't have any trees around, not to
mention fishing and a lot of other quality of life issues,
health,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-22-00 1828 </TRAILER>
