<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S.: No Choice but Force in Miami  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY MARGASAK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite the harrowing photo of a federal agent
with a gun seizing Elian Gonzalez, the Clinton administration
defended its use of force Saturday to take the Cuban boy from the
home of his Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno said she had received information
''there were guns -- perhaps in the crowd, perhaps in the house,''
but the boy's cousin Marisleysis Gonzalez described a chaotic scene
with agents yelling: ''Give me the boy or we're going to shoot.''
</P>
<P>
   The pre-dawn operation immediately was embroiled in presidential
politics, with Republican presidential hopeful George W. Bush
saying ''the chilling picture'' of Elian's removal ''defies the
values of America and is not an image a freedom loving nation wants
to show the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., was even blunter.
''My first thought was that this could only happen in Castro's
Cuba,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The removal of Elian from Lazaro Gonzalez's bedroom was captured
in an Associated Press photo shown around the world. It showed a
federal agent wearing green riot gear, a helmet and goggles with an
automatic rifle confronting a man holding the frightened 6-year-old
boy in a closet.
</P>
<P>
   A switch on the HK MP-5 weapon in photographs is clearly on
''S'' for safety, a position from which it could not be fired.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said that in addition to the intelligence about possible
weapons, those outside the house had previously suggested ''that
they were going to prevent it from happening. Lazaro, who had said
that at one point that he would step aside, said that people might
have to run a gauntlet. And there was clear defiance of the law.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno cast events in the best possible light. she told how a
Spanish-speaking immigration agent spoke soothingly to the boy as
she took him away, using a script worked out in advance. He was
given toys and assured he would not be harmed or put on a boat back
to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   But Marisleysis Gonzalez said there was nothing soothing about
the scene.
</P>
<P>
   ''How can this boy be OK when he had a gun to his head?'' she
asked in anguished tones. She said she told the officers: ''Don't
let the boy see this! I'll give you the boy! Please don't let the
boy see the gun!''
</P>
<P>
   Larry Glick, executive director of the National Tactical
Officers Association, said the officers handled the situation well.
''They didn't send in an overly harsh force,'' he said. ''They
fired chemicals into the crowd first to prevent more serious
injuries. They announced who they were at the door and when the
door was not opened, they did force it open.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton defended his attorney general. ''The law has
been upheld, and that was the right thing to do,'' Clinton he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was no alternative but to enforce the decision'' of the
Immigration and Naturalization Service and of the courts that
custody of the boy should transfer to the father, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was harshly critical.
</P>
<P>
   ''Ours is a nation of laws, not guns,'' Bush said. ''Custody
disputes are resolved in the calm of a courtroom, not in the terror
of middle-of-the-night raids.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno said that ''if you look carefully'' at the picture, ''it
shows that the gun was pointed to the side, and that the finger was
not on the trigger.''
</P>
<P>
   The picture showed the agent's finger not on the trigger, but
just above it.
</P>
<P>
   Eight agents were in the house during the operation, which Reno
said lasted for three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder said, ''We had to make sure
our agents could protect themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-22-00 1828 </TRAILER>
