<HEADLINE> Quotes From the Elian Gonzalez Case  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Quotes from the Elian Gonzalez case:
<TEXT>
<P>
   ''Elian Gonzalez is a child who needs to be cherished, who needs
to have quiet time and private time, and to be with his father. And
that is what this case is still all about -- the bond between a
father and a son.'' -- Attorney General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was no reason to keep him here -- and take him to
Disneyworld. That's not America,'' said Michael Pollizatto, 28, of
Portland, Ore. ''He should be with his father.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I am ashamed. I am so ashamed of what our country did here
tonight. There was no need for this to happen in this fashion.'' --
Miami Mayor Joe Carollo.
</P>
<P>
   ''We thank the millions of Americans who supported this young
father's efforts to be reunited with his most wonderful son.'' --
Gregory Craig, attorney for Juan Miguel Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're angry and disgusted. We were in communication with the
mediator handling negotiations and discussion with the government
when they knocked the door down.'' -- Kendall Coffey, an attorney
for the Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   ''Janet Reno handled this beautifully. I can't stand Clinton,
but he and Reno did a good job on this one. Why shouldn't the man
have his child? There's nothing abhorrent about a child being with
his father.'' -- Bob Burman, a Columbus, Ohio, attorney and father
to two.
</P>
<P>
   ''They took this kid like a hostage in the nighttime.'' -- Donato
Dalrymple, who was holding Elian when federal agents seized him.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a great joy for us. We're filled with satisfaction that
the boy is with his father.'' -- Maura Casanas, 37, an industrial
engineer in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are together.'' -- Myron Marlin, Justice Department
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is terrible. I'm ashamed to be an American. Clinton is a
coward, coward, coward.'' -- Cristina Valdes, 67, protester in
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think what they did is necessary because reuniting him with
his father was necessary.'' -- Carlos Moran, 67, in Havana.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel like I'm back in Cuba in 1960. That's the way I feel
right now. I've been here 40 years. I never, never thought anything
like this would happen.'' -- Beatriz Hernandez, 55, member of
Mothers Against Repression.
</P>
<P>
   ''You've got a family laughing at the attorney general, and
sooner or later you've got to show them some authority. The family
overestimated their position of power.'' -- Roland Rolo, 44, in a
Cuban cafe in Union City, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't believe what I saw. And they want to take our guns
away from us? Why couldn't they just wait another week and let the
boy go peacefully?'' -- Priscilla Talich, mother of a 9-year-old
son, in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ''The kid should be with his father. The people in Miami weren't
going to give the kid up. I don't think they had a choice.'' -- Tom
McClean, 41, an electrician from the Chicago suburb of Woodridge.
</P>
<P>
   ''It looked as though they went to extremes, but we don't know
what led up to that. ... I don't think a child of 6 knows where he
wants to live. I don't think a child of 6 knows politics.'' --
Caroline Tyson, a waitress in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am heartbroken and devastated. I was shocked that a peaceful
transfer, which according to all reports appeared so close, failed
to materialize. It's a real travesty of justice that this had to
come to such a needless and violent transition.'' -- Sister Jeanne
O'Laughlin, who was the host of a meeting between Elian and his
Cuban grandmothers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone talks about Cuba being the evil empire, but how evil
would we be if we kept the boy from his father?'' -- Tim Quistoroff,
34, a musician in Chicago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
