<HEADLINE> Rocket May Be Ukraine Blast Cause  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) -- A military rocket that veered off-course
during training exercises may be to blame for an apartment building
explosion that killed three people, Ukrainian investigators said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Several metal pieces that appeared to have come from a rocket
were found near the damaged building in the town of Brovary, 35
miles from the capital Kiev, the Interfax news agency quoted
investigators as saying.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Ministry said a surface-to-surface rocket was fired
from a training range 80 miles away shortly before Thursday's
explosion and admitted that it deviated from its target -- but said
it was only by 25 yards, Interfax said. Earlier the ministry had
denied the missile left course.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the experts make the final conclusion that the Defense
Ministry is responsible for the blast, the ministry will be the
first to acknowledge it,'' said Defense Ministry spokesman Serhiy
Nahorianskyi, according to Interfax.
</P>
<P>
   The Soviet-designed 9M-79 rocket has an 80-mile range, but was
shooting at a target just 35 miles away, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   Final investigation results are expected Monday, Interfax said.
Police are also investigating whether the explosion was caused by a
bomb.
</P>
<P>
   The blast in a nine-story apartment block sent rafters slamming
through ninth to second floors of the building and forced 91 people
to evacuate. Three were killed and five were injured.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
