<HEADLINE> Serb Opposition Calls for Elections  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Greece (AP) -- Serbian opposition leaders renewed calls
Saturday for early elections and promised greater coordination to
oust Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   More than 90 party leaders, Orthodox clergy and heads of emigre
groups backed the declaration issued at the end of a two-day
meeting here hosted by Aleksandar Karadjordjevic, son of
Yugoslavia's last king, who claims the country's throne.
</P>
<P>
   ''The country and people await changes and it is up to you to
provide leadership for changes. (Otherwise) the country will go to
ruin,'' Karadjordjevic said.
</P>
<P>
   Several leading participants in the talks met on Friday with
James Dobbins, special Balkan adviser to President Clinton, who was
in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia's traditionally fractured opposition agreed to join
forces against Milosevic in January and are pressing calls for
early elections, which are not required to be held until next year.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. and European Union strongly favor early elections and
provide support and funding for Yugoslav opposition groups and
private media. They say sanctions against Yugoslavia will not be
lifted as long as Milosevic is in power.
</P>
<P>
   Greek Foreign Minister George Papandreou on Saturday met a main
opposition leader, Zoran Djindjic, as well as a key group of Kosovo
Serb moderates.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo Serb moderates received his ''full support'' for
their efforts toward ethnic reconciliation in the province,
Papandreou said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Your efforts for survival and cooperation between all the
nationalities of Kosovo are truly heroic,'' Papandreou said after
meeting with members of the group, who included Christian religious
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Papandreou promised aid measures for Kosovo, including accepting
children at Greek summer camps this year.
</P>
<P>
   He said Athens is in ''regular'' contact with both the Yugoslav
government and opposition groups, in an attempt to ease regional
tension.
</P>
<P>
   But the meeting was met with skepticism by many Greeks, who
strongly condemned NATO's bombing of Yugoslavia last year.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of Serb royalists in Athens, also drew criticism in
a country which abolished its own monarchy in a 1974 referendum. A
close aide to Papandreou submitted his resignation Friday after
addressing Karadjordjevic as ''your highness''. Papandreou urged
him to stay on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
