<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Earth Day Celebrated With Exhibits  </HEADLINE>
By BART JANSEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Cindy Bilsky and her family traveled from New
Hampshire to celebrate Earth Day, checking out a varied offering of
politicians, celebrities and environmental lessons on the National
Mall.
</P>
<P>
   Her children, 6-year-old Johnny and 4-year-old Alicia, emerged
smiling from a trailer for the Discovery Creek Children's Museum
that housed butterflies, a tarantula and a monkey in a rainforest
exhibit. The trailer reinforced classroom lessons about the perils
of cutting down all the trees.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's an interesting way to find out how everything is
produced,'' said Bilsky, of Hudson, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   The 30th anniversary Earth Day celebration on the mall featured
tents from the Capitol to the Washington Monument with exhibits
about fighting pollution and using alternative energy sources.
</P>
<P>
   Mascots dressed like Smokey Bear, a bald eagle and a giant panda
roamed the mall and posed for pictures. Pamphleteers distributed
literature on subjects ranging from Ralph Nader's presidential
candidacy to repenting before the end of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrities ranging from teen heartthrob Leonardo DeCaprio to
singer David Crosby contributed to the festive nature of the event.
</P>
<P>
   The Public Interest Research Group, which is fighting to hold
sport-utility vehicles to the same air-pollution standards as cars,
set up a large, inflatable SUV with the sign ''Clean Cars Now!''
</P>
<P>
   Peyton Jackson carried his 3-year-old daughter Casey in a
shoulder pack to listen to the music and learn about recycling. His
6-year-old son Taylor already knows littering is a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   ''Of course, I drove here in my SUV -- but I carpooled,'' said
Jackson, of Alexandria, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Gaylord Nelson, the former senator from Wisconsin who is
credited with startinging Earth Day in 1970, said elementary
students he speaks to about protecting the environment today ask
better questions than college students a generation ago.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that the United States must lead the world to
reduce pollution and renew resources because this country is the
biggest consumer, the biggest polluter and the most affluent in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we don't take the lead,'' he asked, ''who will?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
