<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Opposes India's U.N. Bid  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Pakistan will oppose its arch-foe
India's bid to win a permanent seat on the United Nations' Security
Council, Foreign Minister Abdul Sattar said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   India doesn't deserve Security Council membership because it has
failed to implement U.N. resolutions on the disputed Kashmir
region, Sattar told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Kashmir, a former princely state, is divided between Pakistan
and India and has already been the cause of two of the three wars
those countries have fought since they won independence from
Britain in 1947. Both nations claim the region in its entirety. A
third war between them was fought over Bangladesh, then known as
East Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. resolutions call for a plebiscite among Kashmiris on
which country they wanted to join, something India opposes.
</P>
<P>
   For the last decade, militant Kashmiris have waged a bloody war
against Indian troops in Kashmir, the only Muslim-majority state in
Hindu-dominated India. The militants advocate either merger with
Islamic Pakistan or independence.
</P>
<P>
   India accuses Pakistan of fomenting the secessionist movement, a
charge Pakistan denies.
</P>
<P>
   India wants a permanent seat on the powerful body, whose five
permanent and ten non-permanent members turn U.N. policies into
action. Only the permanent members -- the United States, Britain,
France, China and Russia -- have veto power. The 10 non-permanent
members rotate in two-year stints.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats have for years debated expanding the council, but the
idea has been stalled by disputes over how many seats and which
countries to add.
</P>
<P>
   Sattar said the issue needs in-depth discussions since at least
five African, four Latin American and quite a few Asian countries
are bidding for permanent Security Council seats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-22-00 1912 </TRAILER>
