<HEADLINE> Coach Never Heard Knight Use Slur  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- Cleveland Cavaliers coach Randy Wittman
released a statement saying he never heard Indiana University coach
Bob Knight use a racial slur.
</P>
<P>
   Wittman has become involved in the controversy over the new book
by former Indiana teammate Butch Carter, now the coach of the
Toronto Raptors. In the book, ''Born to Believe,'' Carter claims
Knight used a racial slur.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued Friday by the Cavs, Wittman said, ''In the
five years I was at Indiana, I never heard coach Knight use the
word he is being accused of using. Never. And because of that, none
of the other accusations or issues related to me are credible.
</P>
<P>
   ''My reputation stands for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight is under investigation by university officials for
actions that include physically abusing players.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's allegation has been denied by several former players,
including Wittman, who was singled out in a book excerpt that
appeared in newspapers in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   In the excerpt, Carter said Wittman got upset with him a couple
of years ago at a restaurant because Wittman heard Carter had been
saying Knight is racist.
</P>
<P>
   ''I asked Randy, 'You sat there in the locker room and heard the
same thing I did. What part of it did you not understand?' Even if
he didn't think the comment was racist, and Knight was just having
a bad day?
</P>
<P>
   ''How did I end up getting the blame for what Knight said? I
left there thinking that here's this guy coaching in the NBA and
how is he ever going to be fair to his black players if he takes
that stand on that statement? He did it because of intimidation and
widespread acceptance of Knight's behavior.''
</P>
</TEXT>
