<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Miami Kin Try To See Elian, Dad  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA MARTINEZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Miami relatives of Elian Gonzalez followed him
to Washington on Saturday, hoping for a family reunion and to keep
the 6-year-old boy from going back to Cuba. They were turned away
from the air base gate behind which Elian was reunited with his
father.
</P>
<P>
   The group attempted to hold a news conference outside Andrews
Air Force, but gave up amid a crush of protesters and news media,
saying only that they would make another attempt to see Elian and
his Cuban father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''This family is distraught, and you're not helping matters
any,'' Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H., shouted to the protesters, reporters
and camera crews. ''If you care about them, just please respect
them now.''
</P>
<P>
   The relatives arrived at Reagan National Airport a few hours
after Juan Miguel Gonzalez was reunited with his son under tight
security at Andrews. The boy had been flown from Miami directly to
the air base after being seized from the Miami family by
Immigration and Naturalization Service agents.
</P>
<P>
   The group included Lazaro Gonzalez, who has cared for the boy in
his house for the five months since Elian's rescue at sea; the
cousin who said she was closest to the boy, Marisleysis Gonzalez,
and the fisherman who rescued him, Donato Dalrymple,
</P>
<P>
   They went to the Capitol Hill office of Smith, who accompanied
them to the air base gate. Their five-vehicle motorcade was turned
away, to the protests of a crowd of supporters who had gathered
across the street.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let them in! Let them in!'' the crowd shouted.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he was not barred from the base personally as a
senator but was barred as part of a group. He said they were not
necessarily asking to meet with Elian and his father Saturday
night, but wanted to be on the base in a place ''where we could sit
down and gather ourselves together'' and possibly get a time for a
family meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Smith described his meeting with the family as an
emotional moment.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're beside themselves with grief ... I never thought I'd
see this in America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Presidential spokesman Joe Lockhart indicated the group likely
would not succeed in any effort to see President Clinton, who left
Saturday for the Camp David retreat. ''The president believes the
appropriate place in our government for them to go is the Justice
Department of the INS (Immigration and Naturalization Service,''
Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of the crowd outside the air base backed the Miami
family.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's clear ... that the majority of the people support the
reunion of the boy with his father,'' said Sarah Manning of
Baltimore, who held up a sign saying ''Congratulations,'' aimed at
Elian and his father.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
