<HEADLINE> Honolulu Newspaper Up for Sale  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONOLULU (AP) -- The Honolulu Star-Bulletin is being put up for
sale.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty Newspapers, the owner of the afternoon newspaper,
announced Saturday that it has agreed to offer it for sale.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement approved by U.S. District Court Judge Alan Kay was
reached in negotiations to settle lawsuits filed by the state and a
citizens group against Liberty and Gannett Pacific Corp., owner of
the morning Honolulu Advertiser. The lawsuits will remain in effect
until the newspaper is sold.
</P>
<P>
   Once the sale of the Star-Bulletin in completed, Liberty and
Gannett will conclude their business relationship, and the pending
lawsuits will be dismissed, the announcement said.
</P>
<P>
   If the newspaper doesn't sell, all parties retain their rights
to continue litigating, according to Star-Bulletin managing
director David Shapiro.
</P>
<P>
   A stipulation filed in federal court provides for sale of the
daily's assets to a new owner that would publish it apart from the
Honolulu Advertiser.
</P>
<P>
   The buyer will be required to continue publishing the
Star-Bulletin. A proposed sale price was not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The Star-Bulletin, which shares office space with the Advertiser
in a Gannett-owned building, would have to find new quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The new owner also would have to set up separate circulation,
advertising, accounting and other operational functions.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of the two newspapers entered an agreement last September
to end their joint operating agreement on Oct. 30 and close the
Star-Bulletin. The plan was for Gannett to pay Liberty $26.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   Kay issued a preliminary injunction to stop the closure after
the lawsuits were filed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-22-00 2043 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000422.0121 </DOCNO>
