<HEADLINE> Saturday's Baseball Notebook  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Yankees-Blue Jays:
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO: Blue Jays players watched the White Sox-Tigers brawl on
a clubhouse TV. Jose Cruz Jr. and Carlos Delgado each cut
interviews short to see it, and the fracas interrupted a card game
between Billy Koch, Marty Cordova, Craig Grebeck and Lance Painter.
''That's the brawl of the year,'' Painter said. ... Brad Fullmer
has 14 hits and 14 RBIs in his last 27 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: 3B Scott Brosius, on the disabled list with a pulled
rib muscle, went 0-for-1 with a walk Saturday in his first
rehabilitation start for the Tampa Yankees of the Florida State
League. He cleanly handled two chances in the field. ''My only
purpose right now is to get out here and test my side and see how
it feels against live pitching,'' he said. ''If all goes well, I'll
be back with the big team in a couple of days. I'll play here in
Tampa through Monday, then possibly go north to join the team on
Tuesday.'' ... SS Derek Jeter is battling the flu. ... Jason
Grimsley, making his first appearance since April 12, retired all
nine hitters he faced.
Angels-Devil Rays:
</P>
<P>
   ANAHEIM: RHP Tim Belcher (elbow surgery), who is expected back
early next month, will make at least one start at Triple-A
Edmonton. He threw five innings Thursday for Class A Elsinore.
</P>
<P>
   TAMPA BAY: LHP Wilson Alvarez continues to be slowed by left
shoulder stiffness and will not play catch again until Monday. ...
RHP Juan Guzman (right shoulder) is also out indefinitely. There is
no timetable for when he will resume throwing.
Twins-Rangers:
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: Manager Tom Kelly is six victories short of 1,000 for
his career. Kelly was named Twins manager on Sept. 12, 1986, making
him the most tenured manager or head coach in pro sports.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS: The Rangers haven't been below .500 after 16 games since
starting 6-10 in 1995. Texas, which lost seven of its first 11 at
home, hadn't been three games under .500 at home after 11 games
since going 4-7 in 1995.
Tigers-White Sox:
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: RHP Brian Moehler was scratched from Sunday's scheduled
start against the White Sox after an emergency appendectomy. He
reported to Comiskey Park on Saturday for the Tigers' game against
Chicago, then was taken to Christ Hospital in Oak Lawn for surgery.
RHP Dave Borkowski was to be called up from Triple-A Toledo to take
Moehler's place in the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: The White Sox are off to their best 17-game start since
1994 when they also began 11-6.
Royals-Mariners:
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: Brett Tomko is 7-0 lifetime against AL teams. With
Cincinnati, he was 6-0 in games against AL clubs. All his decisions
have been against AL Central teams. ''I don't like to talk about
that stat too much,'' Tomko said. ''You kind of laugh at it. No, I
don't put too many thoughts into it.'' ... Mike Cameron (bruised
left knee) and Edgar Martinez (sore left quadriceps muscle) are
expected to play Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: Kansas City's eight-game losing streak is its
longest since last season when it dropped nine in a row. The
Royals' longest losing skid ever is 12 in 1997. ... CF Johnny Damon
came out of Saturday's game in the fifth inning with a sprained
middle finger of his right hand. He hurt himself sliding back into
first in the first on an attempted pickoff play.
Orioles-Athletics:
</P>
<P>
   BALTIMORE: RHP Jason Johnson, recalled from Triple-A Rochester
on Friday, is to make his first start of the season Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: Gil Heredia has walked 13 batters in his first four
starts, an average of 4.68 per nine innings. He walked an AL-low
average of 1.53 last season.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Cubs-Mets:
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: Kerry Wood makes what could be his final rehab start
Sunday for Triple-A Iowa. Wood is expected to return to the Cubs
for the first time since undergoing reconstructive elbow surgery on
their homestand that begins next Friday. ... Damon Buford broke an
0-for-16 slump with a single in the opener. ... Baylor said when he
played in Boston that Wade Boggs threw batting practice on days
knuckleballers pitched. ''His was just as tough as Phil Niekro's or
Charlie Hough's,'' Baylor said. Because of the wet field, the Cubs
had to settle for hitting in the batting cage before facing Dennis
Springer.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: Rick Reed will likely miss his start Monday because he
cannot wear a glove because of an injured left wrist. ''You can't
pitch if you can't defend yourself,'' Mets manager Bobby Valentine
said. Pat Mahomes will likely get the start unless he is needed in
relief on Sunday.
Brewers-Expos:
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: Mark Loretta returned to the lineup for Saturday
night's game, playing shortstop and batting second. Loretta didn't
start Friday night, though he was available off the bench, after
leaving Thursday night's 5-4 loss in New York with a mild
concussion after colliding with OF James Mouton while fielding a
foul pop in the sixth. ... The Brewers were trying to avoid losing
six straight for the first time since last July 31-Aug. 6.
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: RF Vladimir Guerrero entered Saturday night's game
with 99 career homers. Guerrero is tied with Larry Walker for
seventh place on the Expos' home run leader list, one behind Larry
Parrish. Andre Dawson's 225 homers from 1976-86 are the most by an
Expo, followed by Gary Carter (220) and Larry Parrish (204). ...
Mike Thurman made 61 pitches in a three-inning rehab outing for
Class A Jupiter Friday. Thurman, who is on the 15-day disabled list
with right elbow tendinitis, allowed two runs and seven hits and
took the loss as the Hammerheads fell 16-3 to Brevard County.
Phillies-Marlins:
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: Brian Hunter, who was signed by the Phils on
Friday, made his first appearance and start in place of first
baseman Rico Brogna, who was hit by Vladimir Nunez on Friday. He
singled in his second at-bat but was then picked off. Brogna
sustained a contusion on the right knee but was available to
pinch-hit Saturday . ... C Tom Prince made his second start of the
season in place of All-Star catcher Mike Lieberthal. ... Sunday's
starter Robert Person is 2-0 at Pro Player with an 0.53 ERA. In
four games, he's given up just one run in 17 innings.
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: The Marlins placed 2B Luis Castillo on the disabled
list due to a lower back strain. The move is retroactive to April
16. Castillo, off to the best start of his career, was hitting .333
with a .500 on-base percentage. He had missed the previous six
games. ... The team purchased the contract of infielder Pablo Ozuna
from Double-A Portland. Ozuna was hitting .349. Boles said he would
probably start him on Sunday, but not in the leadoff spot where
Castillo has been excelling. ... The Marlins assigned the contract
of utility infielder Dave Berg to Brevard County (Class A) to
continue rehabilitation of his shoulder. ... Marlins owner John
Henry said that with no prospect of a new ballpark and a potential
revenue loss of $15 million to $20 million next year, he would
unload the higher-priced players in a similar fashion that his
predecessor, H. Wayne Huizenga, did following the 1997 World Series
championship season. ''You've seen a lot of teams spending years
trying to solve their ballpark situation, Montreal and Minnesota,
but if we're going to take that approach, we have to continually
start over rebuilding this team,'' Henry said. ''For us, patience
means a number of years of non-competitive baseball.''
Dodgers-Reds:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: RHP Kevin Brown, who broke the small finger on his
right hand while bunting on April 8, threw in the bullpen Saturday.
If he gets through another bullpen session Sunday without problem,
he will be activated and start Tuesday in Atlanta. ... Since
hitting three homers in San Francisco on April 11, Kevin Elster has
gone 8-for-26 (.308) with five homers and 10 RBIs. ... Gary
Sheffield has homered in five of his last seven games while hitting
.382.
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: SS Barry Larkin had thick wrapping on his left hand
Saturday, protecting his surgically repaired middle finger. Larkin,
who tore tissue in the finger Friday night, will wear a brace on
his left hand for 10 days and can start gripping objects again in
two weeks. ... Norm Charlton's wild pitch in the ninth gave the
Reds 18 wild pitches in 18 games, most in the majors. The NL record
for wild pitches in a season is 91, shared by Houston (1970) and
Philadelphia (1989). The Reds hold the league record for fewest
wild pitches in a season -- nine in 1944.
Pirates-Braves:
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH: Starting pitcher Kris Benson is a 1994 graduate of
Sprayberry High School in Marietta, an Atlanta suburb. ... Jason
Kendall led off for the 16th time this season, the most by a
catcher since Craig Biggio batted first in 17 games for Houston in
1989. ... John Vander Wal, who started in right field, already has
two pinch-hit homers, two away from the team's season record set by
Mark Johnson in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: Streaking Andres Galarraga got the night off with a day
game Sunday. Wally Joyner started at first base. ... Bobby Bonilla
has started 12 of 17 games in left field. Reggie Sanders is
struggling, hitting .154 with no homers and one RBI in 65 at-bats
prior to Saturday's game. ... John Burkett, signed just before
opening day, made his first start of the season. He went 0-2 with
an 11.81 ERA out of the bullpen. ... Wednesday's game against the
Los Angeles Dodgers was switched from 7:40 to 7:05 p.m. to
accommodate ESPN.
Padres-Astros:
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO: The Padres activated C Carlos Hernandez from the
15-day disabled list and optioned OF Mike Darr to Triple-A Las
Vegas. Hernandez had been out since April 7 because of a strained
right groin. Darr hit .077 (1-for-13) with two RBI and three walks
in five games. Hernandez was in the starting lineup Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON: The Astros (6-9) entered Saturday's game four games
behind the division-leading Cardinals, Houston's largest deficit
since Sept. 29, 1996.
Rockies-Cardinals:
</P>
<P>
   COLORADO: Before the game, the Rockies reinstated OF Jeffrey
Hammonds from the 15-day disabled list and designated OF Jeff Manto
for assignment. Hammonds, who injured his hamstring doubling in the
ninth inning on opening day, was in the lineup batting sixth and
playing left field. ... The Rockies have won the opener all four
series but entered Saturday's game 2-4 in the second game of the
series. ... Reliever Gabe White had allowed five of six inherited
runners to score.
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: OF Jim Edmonds, among the league leaders in batting
(.386) and six other offensive categories, got his first day off
due to a strain in his left foot. He blamed a new pair of shoes he
wore during batting practice for the injury. ''They felt a little
tight,'' Edmonds said. ''In the seventh inning, all of a sudden it
just got really bad.'' Team doctors told Edmonds he probably could
play Sunday. ... Reserve Thomas Howard had 12 RBIs and three home
runs in his first 17 at-bats. ... The Cardinals outscored their
opponents 31-13 in the first inning the first 17 games.
Giants-Diamondbacks:
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO: San Francisco assured itself of its first series
victory against Arizona since Sept. 12-14, 1998. ... Robb Nen
allowed his first hit and walk of the season but also struck out
the side. He has seven strikeouts in five innings.
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA: Luis Gonzalez has hit 14 of his 30 homers with Arizona
at home. ... Byung-Hung Kim had pitched seven scoreless innings
before the Giants scored three runs against him.
</P>
