<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sunshine Street Ousts Single Empire  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. (AP) -- Horses trained by Neil Drysdale finished
first and second in Santa Anita Park's San Juan Capistrano
Invitational Handicap on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   But Sunshine Street upset 7-10 favorite Single Empire in the
$400,000 race.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine Street, the 2-1 second choice, edged Single Empire by
two lengths in the 1}-mile grass marathon, with a time of 2:49.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Bailey flew to California from Florida to ride Sunshine
Street -- a 5-year-old bay -- to his third successive victory. But it
was his first win in a graded stakes race. It deprived Single
Empire and jockey Kent Desormeaux of back-to-back wins in North
America's longest Grade I turf event.
</P>
<P>
   Bailey rallied Sunshine Street on the outside of three horses
turning into the stretch. Single Empire managed to squeeze through
an opening at the three-eighths pole, but failed to match strides
with the winner.
</P>
<P>
   Chelsea Barracks, who set the early pace under Matt Garcia, held
on for third, one-length farther back in the field of five. He was
followed by Star Performance and Company Approval. Jack Grandi was
a late scratch.
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine Street, 115 pounds, paid $6.20, $2.60 and $2.40. Single
Empire returned $2.20 and $2.20 while Chelsea Barracks paid $3 to
show.
</P>
<P>
   Desormeaux declined comment to reporters after the race, but
Drysdale relayed the rider's observations.
</P>
<P>
   ''Kent said that when he came through at the three-eighths pole,
he got hammered,'' Drysdale said. ''He felt it kind of knocked the
breath out of the horse. He ran the rest of the way on guts.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey, meanwhile, had a clear trip on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   ''I did take a beating going around the turn, as far as losing
ground was concerned,'' Bailey said, ''but he was going so
smoothly, I didn't want to change it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunshine Street earned $240,000 for owner Pat Garvey after
accumulating $380,298 in 19 previous starts. The victory was only
his fourth win to accompany seven seconds and a third.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
