<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DiCaprio-Clinton Interview Short  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER, AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- After all the fuss, Leonardo DiCaprio's debut in
a news role was a bit part.
</P>
<P>
   The actor's 20-minute chat in the White House with President
Clinton about global warming was edited down to two minutes on
ABC's Saturday special, ''Planet Earth 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   DiCaprio was seen asking the president three questions.
</P>
<P>
   The interview prompted a flood of criticism from people --
including some within ABC News -- who wondered why the hunky
''Titanic'' star was being sent to do a journalist's job.
</P>
<P>
   Not only was DiCaprio playing the role of a reporter, he was
playing the role of a reporter with a conflict of interest. He's
chairman of the Earth Day 2000 celebration committee and approached
ABC with the idea of a special on global warming.
</P>
<P>
   ABC executives, who said they enlisted DiCaprio to entice young
viewers to a news show, were embarrassed when they originally said
the actor visited Clinton at the White House's request without the
understanding of an interview. But the White House said ABC asked
for an interview ahead of time.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're trying something different,'' newswoman Elizabeth
Vargas, enlisted as host in the past two weeks to give the show
some journalistic heft, said in introducing DiCaprio.
</P>
<P>
   The actor filmed segments in a frog habitat in Los Angeles and a
butterfly museum in New York City that were used to begin and end
the show, and introduce individual segments.
</P>
<P>
   His interview with Clinton wasn't shown until 52 minutes of the
hour-long special had passed.
</P>
<P>
   DiCaprio thanked Clinton for the opportunity to talk about
global warming, saying he was ''neither a politician or a
journalist. It was an opportunity as a concerned citizen I couldn't
pass up.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Why do you think this issue is so constantly overlooked?'' he
asked Clinton. ''Why do you think people don't take it seriously?
For you, is it as important as something like health care or
education?''
</P>
<P>
   He also asked what Clinton thought was the best course for
American citizens over the next 20 years to help the environment.
</P>
<P>
   His final question: ''Do you think we can eventually become a
role model?''
</P>
<P>
   DiCaprio was reportedly helped by something common to actors but
less so to journalists -- the opportunity for retakes. New Yorker
magazine said this week that ABC filmed DiCaprio later asking again
some of his questions after he flubbed his lines, and it was then
spliced into the footage.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's attempt to appeal to younger viewers was evident
throughout the show, which used video tricks like speeding up the
picture, slowing it down or blurring it. Vargas, filmed in a New
Mexico desert, was dressed in fashionable black shirt and black
slacks, with a denim jacket.
</P>
<P>
   The news special also had a trendy techno soundtrack, with one
odd exception: a brief snippet of '60s rockers Jefferson Airplane.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-22-00 2152 </TRAILER>
