<HEADLINE> Brewers 7, Expos 3  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL (AP) -- Geoff Jenkins homered for the second straight
game and added a two-run double as the Milwaukee Brewers stopped a
five-game losing streak by beating the Montreal Expos 7-3 Saturday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Everett Stull (1-1) got his first major league win, allowing two
runs and nine hits in five-plus innings. He gave up consecutive
homers by Lee Stevens and Chris Widger leading off the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Milwaukee had a season-high 15 hits to send Montreal to just its
second loss in its last seven games at Olympic Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins, who homered off Hideki Irabu (1-2) leading off the
second, doubled off Steve Kline with runners at second and third in
the seventh to make it 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Belliard was 2-for-4 with a homer and two RBIs, and Kevin
Barker had a pair of run-scoring doubles.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu, making his first career appearance against Milwaukee,
allowed five runs and 10 hits in 6 1-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins hit his sixth homer off leading off the second and the
Brewers added a second run on Barker's RBI double.
</P>
<P>
   Belliard homered leading off the fourth to make it 3-0 and,
after Jose Hernandez singled with one out, Barker delivered his
second straight run-scoring double.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal closed to 4-2 in the bottom half when Stevens led off
with his third homer and Widger followed with his second of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Guerrero scored the Expos' third run on a strange play
in the sixth to draw Montreal within one.
</P>
<P>
   Guerrero singled leading off to chase Stull, and advanced on
Chris Widger's one-out single off Jim Bruske.
</P>
<P>
   Both runners moved up on Michael Barrett's grounder to
shortstop, and Guerrero came home on Orlando Cabrera's sharply-hit
grounder to third. Hernandez ran down Widger for the third out,
after electing not to throw to first.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Barker's doubles were his first two of the season. ... Mark
Loretta returned to the Brewers' lineup, playing shortstop and
batting second. Loretta didn't start Friday night, though he was
available off the bench, after leaving Thursday night's 5-4 loss in
New York with a mild concussion. ... Guerrero is tied with Larry
Walker for seventh on the Expos' career homer list at 99, one
behind Larry Parrish. Andre Dawson's 225 homers from 1976-86 are
the most by an Expo, followed by Gary Carter (220) and Larry
Parrish (204). ... Mike Thurman made 61 pitches in a three-inning
rehab outing for Class-A Jupiter on Friday. Thurman, who is on the
15-day disabled list with right elbow tendinitis, allowed two runs
and seven hits and took the loss as the Hammerheads fell 16-3 to
Brevard County.
</P>
</TEXT>
