<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, April 22, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian Gonzalez and Dad Reunited
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ANDREWS AIR FORCE BASE, Md. (AP) -- Elian Gonzalez was in seclusion with his
father, stepmother, and baby half-brother at Andrews Air Force base outside
Washington tonight, after being taken from his Miami relatives' home by federal
agents in a pre-dawn raid. At 5 a.m., more than 20 agents in white vans arrived
at the house of Lazaro Gonzalez, the boy's great-uncle, and used battering rams
to get through the home's chain-link fence and front door. Though in his
father's custody, Elian's fate still remains unsettled. The courts will
ultimately rule on whether the boy should remain in the United States.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
230 Arrested in Miami; Cubans Celebrate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- More than 230 people were arrested and more than 207 fires were
set today by protesters on the streets of Little Havana after Elian Gonzalez was
snatched away by federal agents. Riot police with batons and shields beat down
demonstrators who set bonfires and uprooted concrete benches. As Miami mayors
called for calm, an angry crowd tore down the CNN tent at the house where Elian
had lived. In Cuba, Elian's Cuban relatives joined hundreds of thousands who
streamed down a muddy road to a historic sugar refinery to celebrate the boy's
reunion with his father. ''Elian, friend! Cuba is with you!'' chanted an
estimated 400,000 people called by Cuba's communist government to gather at
Central Australia.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Miami Kin Try To See Elian, Dad
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Miami relatives of Elian Gonzalez followed him to
Washington today, hoping to keep the 6-year-old boy from going back to Cuba.
They were turned away from the air base gate behind which Elian was reunited
with his father. The group attempted to hold a news conference outside Andrews
Air Force, but gave up amid a crush of protesters and news media, saying only
that they would make another attempt to see Elian and his Cuban father, Juan
Miguel Gonzalez, on Sunday. The group included Lazaro Gonzalez, who has cared
for the boy in his house for the five months since Elian's rescue at sea; cousin
Marisleysis Gonzalez, and the fisherman who rescued him, Donato Dalrymple.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Calif. Summons Insurance Execs
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Accused of mishandling claims from the 1994
earthquake in Los Angeles, executives from six insurance companies were summoned
to the state Insurance Department's headquarters. They were ushered into an
office one by one and offered a choice: Donate to a new fund set up by the
department or face billions of dollars' worth of penalties. Ultimately, the
insurers decided to avoid the penalties and gave the fund a total of $11.6
million in donations for education, consumer assistance and earthquake research.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Explosion Rocks Zimbabwe Newspaper
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- An explosion shook the offices of Zimbabwe's only
independent newspaper Saturday in a suspected bomb attack. Zimbabwe has been
roiled in recent months by political violence, particularly attacks on
opposition supporters, and the often-violent occupation of white-owned farm by
black squatters. The explosion, near the staff entrance to the building housing
The Daily News, caused little damage but shattered the windows of a neighboring
sculpture gallery. The building was empty, since the newspaper does not print on
weekends.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Noise, Stale Air Await Astronauts
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- When astronauts float into the international
space station this week, they'll be armed with ear plugs, air monitors and fans
because the Russian side of the Russian space station is still too noisy because
of acoustic design. In addition to the racket 225 miles up, the air is stale and
the ventilation bad -- bad enough to sicken the last astronauts who visited the
space station, last spring. So this next crew will tote small, personal fans and
carbon-dioxide monitors. Six Americans and one Russian are scheduled to lift off
aboard space shuttle Atlantis on Monday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
N.Y. Senate Race: Most Expensive?
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton and New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani are on a pace to shatter the the record for the most expensive U.S.
Senate race in history. California set the bar in 1994 when Diane Feinstein and
Michael Huffington spent $43.3 million; New Yorkers Alfonse D'Amato and Charles
Schumer spent $40.9 million in 1998. Clinton and Giuliani have raked in more
than $32 million so far, federal campaign finance records show, and the election
is still seven months away.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Jazz Defeat SuperSonics 104-93
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Karl Malone scored a career playoff-high 50 points,
breaking a 16-year-old Utah team record as the Jazz beat Seattle 104-93 today in
Game 1 of the best-of-five series. The 36-year-old forward was in classic form,
almost unstoppable in the second half as he scored 26 points. His 50 points came
on 18-of-32 shooting and he added 12 rebounds in 43 minutes. Jeff Hornacek added
13 points and John Stockton had 10 for the Jazz.
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA 
</P>
</TEXT>
