<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-22 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elian and Dad Reunite on Airplane  </HEADLINE>
By DEB RIECHMANN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- It ended with a bear hug in the aisle of an
airplane. Elian and his father -- finally reunited.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly five months, 6-year-old Elian and his father, Juan
Miguel Gonzalez, have been entangled in an international custody
fight that transformed them into heroes in America and their native
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Their separation ended Saturday morning. When the plane carrying
Elian landed at Andrews Air Force Base outside Washington, Gonzalez
boarded it alone and spent five minutes with the son he hadn't seen
since before Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   When they emerged from the plane, Elian was wrapped in a
blanket, said Maria Cardona, a spokeswoman for the Immigration and
Naturalization Service. Elian's arms ringed his father's neck. His
head rested on his daddy's shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was very, very moving,'' INS Commissioner Doris Meissner
said. ''It was very touching.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither father nor son had gotten much sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, 31, had spent most of Friday night negotiating with
the boy's Miami relatives. They wanted to retain custody of Elian,
who was found holding on an inner tube floating off the Florida
coast on Nov. 25 after a boat sank. His mother and 10 others died
in the attempt to escape from communist Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   When negotiations broke down, U.S. government agents raided the
relatives' home in Miami early Saturday, retrieved the boy and flew
him to the Air Force base where the reunion took place.
</P>
<P>
   Snapshots recorded the emotional day.
</P>
<P>
   In one, Gonzalez holds Elian, who is wearing a light blue Batman
T-shirt. Side-by-side, their resemblance cannot be mistaken. Father
and son's eyebrows arch over the same deep-brown eyes. Their smiles
are nearly identical.
</P>
<P>
   In another photo, Elian sits on the floor, cradling his
6-month-old half-brother, Hianny, on his lap. Elian's eyes ''lit
up'' when he saw his baby brother, according to the Rev. Joan Brown
Campbell, who has been in touch with the Gonzalez family in both
the United States and Cuba. She said Elian remarked: ''He's gotten
so big since I saw him.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian's trip to Andrews was his first time on an airplane.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Elian colored, played with Play-Doh and fell
asleep on the lap of INS Agent Betty Mills, who is fluent in
Spanish, Cardona said. Also aboard was a flight surgeon and a
psychiatrist, both from the U.S. Public Health Service.
</P>
<P>
   ''The boy appeared to be very calm throughout the flight,''
Cardona said. ''In one of the legs of the flight, he became a
little upset. He started to cry a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   To help soothe him, the INS agents opened a window shade and
urged him to gaze outside ''at the pretty colors in the sky,''
Cardona said.
</P>
<P>
   At Andrews, he went into a home on the base where he joined his
stepmother, Nersy, and baby brother. Mills and Jim Goldman, the
other INS agent on the flight, reported that when they left the
house, Elian was ''happily playing on the floor like any
6-year-old,'' Cardona said.
</P>
<P>
   Elian also politely shook hands with his daddy's lawyer, Greg
Craig, who said he was surprised at the small stature of the boy,
who has become a giant-sized folk figure whose plight prompted
demonstrations in two nations.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you really see this little boy, you realize how small he
is physically,'' Craig said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-22-00 2220 </TRAILER>
