<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Braves 4, Pirates 2  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL NEWBERRY, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Andruw Jones homered, Bruce Chen pitched three
scoreless innings in relief and the Atlanta Braves won their sixth
in a row Saturday night, 4-2 over the Pittsburgh Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   John Rocker, coming on to another standing ovation, struck out
the side in the ninth for his second save. After allowing a two-out
singles to Pat Meares, he fanned Brian Giles on a checked-swing.
</P>
<P>
   Chen (2-0) took over in the fourth after starter John Burkett
was injured the previous inning. The left-hander, making his first
appearance since being recalled from the minors Thursday night,
allowed three hits and struck out three.
</P>
<P>
   Jones broke a 1-1 tie in the fifth, knocking a hanging slider
into the left-field seats for his fourth homer of the season. He
has hit in 13 of 14 games, including six in a row.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves extended their lead in the sixth. Wally Joyner,
starting at first in place of the streaking Andres Galarraga, led
off with a single to left and moved to third on Bobby Bonilla's
double.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Weiss walked to load the bases before pinch-hitter Keith
Lockhart brought home the run with a slow grounder to second.
Warren Morris got the force at second, but Lockhart beat Meares'
relay throw to first.
</P>
<P>
   Pittsburgh closed to 3-2 in the seventh on Kevin Young's RBI
groundout against Luis Rivera. But Mike Remlinger came on to get
the final out, and the Braves pushed the margin back to two runs in
the eighth when pinch-runner Rafael Furcal sprinted home on a wild
pitch by Jose Silva.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta went ahead in the first, leading off with three straight
hits against Kris Benson (0-3). Brian Jordan struck out with the
bases loaded but Joyner made it 1-0 with a sacrifice fly to right.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates tied it up in the third, taking advantage of two
walks by Burkett. Kevin Young followed with an RBI single to left
before the Atlanta starter got out of the inning by striking out
John Vander Wal and getting Wil Cordero on a grounder.
</P>
<P>
   Burkett, making his first start of the season, was hurt during
the third and left the game with a stuff right shoulder, an injury
not thought to be serious.
</P>
<P>
   Benson, a native of suburban Marietta, allowed seven hits,
walked two and struck out four. He also started slowly last year,
going 1-2 with a 5.06 ERA in April.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Mike Remlinger has retired the first hitter in all 11 of
his appearances this season. ... The crowd of 41,389 was the
largest at Turner Field since opening day. ... Cordero had an
embarrassing play in the fourth, dropping a fly ball by Bonilla at
the edge of the warning track in left. Benson was able to pitch
around the miscue. ... Galarraga came on in the eighth as a
pinch-hitter. He struck out to end his seven-game hitting streak.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
