<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Saturday, April 22, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian Gonzalez and Dad Reunited
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ANDREWS AIR FORCE BASE, Md. (AP) -- After being taken from his Miami
relatives' home by federal agents in a pre-dawn raid, Elian Gonzalez was in
seclusion tonight with his father, stepmother and baby half-brother at Andrews
Air Force base outside Washington. At 5 a.m., more than 20 agents in white vans
arrived at the house of Lazaro Gonzalez, the boy's great-uncle, and used
battering rams to get through the home's chain-link fence and front door. Though
in his father's custody, Elian's fate still remains unsettled. The courts will
ultimately rule on whether the boy should remain in the United States.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cubans Celebrate; 260 Arrested in Miami
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   CENTRAL AUSTRALIA, Cuba (AP) -- ''Today is a truce,'' between Cuba and the
United States, Fidel Castro declared today, praising U.S. Attorney General Janet
Reno and INS officials for reuniting Elian Gonzalez with his father. As the
child's grandparents joined hundreds of thousands of Cubans in celebration,
Castro proclaimed the boy's return to his father's arms a reprieve in the
conflict between Cuba and the United States. In Little Havana in Miami, more
than 260 people were arrested and more than 207 fires were set today by
protesters on the streets of Little Havana after Elian Gonzalez was snatched
away by federal agents. Riot police with batons and shields beat down
demonstrators who set bonfires and uprooted concrete benches.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Airplane reunion for Elian and Father
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- After nearly five months, 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez and
his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, entangled in an international custody fight,
finally reunited. When the plane carrying Elian landed at Andrews Air Force Base
outside Washington, Gonzalez boarded it alone and spent five minutes with the
son he hadn't seen since before Thanksgiving. When they emerged from the plane,
Elian was wrapped in a blanket, said Maria Cardona, a spokeswoman for the
Immigration and Naturalization Service. Elian's head rested on his daddy's
shoulders.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Calif. Summons Insurance Execs
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Accused of mishandling claims from the 1994
earthquake in Los Angeles, executives from six insurance companies were summoned
to the state Insurance Department's headquarters. They were ushered into an
office one by one and offered a choice: Donate to a new fund set up by the
department or face billions of dollars' worth of penalties. Ultimately, the
insurers decided to avoid the penalties and gave the fund a total of $11.6
million in donations for education, consumer assistance and earthquake research.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Explosion Rocks Zimbabwe Newspaper
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- An explosion shook the offices of Zimbabwe's only
independent newspaper Saturday in a suspected bomb attack. Zimbabwe has been
roiled in recent months by political violence, particularly attacks on
opposition supporters, and the often-violent occupation of white-owned farm by
black squatters. The explosion, near the staff entrance to the building housing
The Daily News, caused little damage but shattered the windows of a neighboring
sculpture gallery. The building was empty, since the newspaper does not print on
weekends.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Two Planes Crash in Va.; 7 Dead
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NORTON, Va. (AP) -- Five members of a family were found dead in the wreckage
of a small plane in the hills of southwestern Virginia today, more than a day
after the plane disappeared from radar, officials said. The single-engine Mooney
20G aircraft was en route from Nashville, Tenn., to Roanoke when it vanished
from radar late Friday morning near Norton. The cause of the crash was not
immediately known, but Virginia State Trooper Dan Helton said initial
investigations suggest the plane was flying too low and hit several tree tops
before going down. Also today, two people were killed when a small airplane
crashed in Shenandoah County in northwest Virginia, state police said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
DiCaprio-Clinton Interview Short
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- After all the fuss, actor Leonardo DiCaprio's 20-minute chat
in the White House with President Clinton about global warming was edited down
to two minutes on ABC's Saturday special, ''Planet Earth 2000.'' DiCaprio was
seen asking the president three questions. The interview prompted a flood of
criticism from people -- including some within ABC News -- who wondered why the
hunky ''Titanic'' star was being sent to do a journalist's job. DiCaprio is
chairman of the Earth Day 2000 celebration committee and approached ABC with the
idea of a special on global warming.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Maple Leafs Defeat Senators 2-1 in OT
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Steve Thomas scored twice, including the game-winner 14:47
into overtime tonight, to lead the Toronto Maple Leafs to a 2-1 victory over the
Ottawa Senators. Thomas put the Leafs ahead 3-2 in the best-of-7 first-round
playoff series. With a win at Ottawa on Monday, Toronto can advance to a
second-round meeting with the New Jersey Devils.
AP NewsBrief by RICHARD A. SOMMA 
</P>
